le.com/t_backup_vldb.htm|title=Oracle Backup VLDB tips|website=Burleson Consulting|date=26 March 2015|access-date=11 October 2016|first=Donald|last=Burleson\n|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630223240/http://www.dba-oracle.com/t_backup_vldb.htm|archive-date=30 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ISACA-BKBP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.isaca.org/Journal/archives/2012/Volume-1/Pages/Database-Backup-and-Recovery-Best-Practices.aspx\n|title=Database Backup and Recovery Best Practices|first1=Ali Navid|last1=Akhtar|first2=Jeff|last2=Buchholtz|first3=Michael|last3=Ryan|first4=Kumar|last4= Setty|date=2012|access-date=12 October 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629131442/https://www.isaca.org/Journal/archives/2012/Volume-1/Pages/Database-Backup-and-Recovery-Best-Practices.aspx|archive-date=29 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MYSQL-HA-SCALE\">{{cite web|url=https://dev.mysql.com/doc/mysql-ha-scalability/en/ha-overview.html|access-date=12 October 2018\n|title=Chapter 1 High Availability and Scalability|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|website=dev.mysql\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161215030829/https://dev.mysql.com/doc/mysql-ha-scalability/en/ha-overview.html|archive-date=15 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CERN-ORA-PART\">{{cite speech|title=Get the best out of Oracle Partitioning - A practical guide and reference|first1=Thomas|last=Teske|others=Hermann B\u00e4r\n|url=https://indico.cern.ch/event/697301/attachments/1598206/2532649/Partitioning_guide_v18.pdf|publisher=Oracle|website=Cern|location=40-S2-C01 - Salle Curie (CERN)|date=8 Feb 2018|access-date=12 October 2018\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012172456/https://indico.cern.ch/event/697301/attachments/1598206/2532649/Partitioning_guide_v18.pdf\n|archive-date=12 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> <!-- See also https://indico.cern.ch/event/697301 -->\n\n<ref name=\"OraPart12cR2WP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oracle.com/technetwork/database/options/partitioning/partitioning-wp-12c-1896137.pdf\n|title=Oracle Partitioning in Oracle Database 12c Release 2 Extreme Data Management and Performance for every System|date=March 2017|access-date=17 October 2018|website=Oracle\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215074909/https://www.oracle.com/technetwork/database/options/partitioning/partitioning-wp-12c-1896137.pdf\n|url-access=limited|url-status=live|archive-date=15 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Shrestha\">{{cite conference|conference=7th International Conference on Cloud Computing and Services\n|title=High Availability and Performance of Database in the Cloud - Traditional Master-slave Replication versus Modern Cluster-based Solutions\n|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/317299391\n|first=Raju|last=Shrestha|doi=10.5220/0006294604130420|isbn=978-989-758-243-1|date=2017|volume=1: CLOSER|publisher= SCITEPRESS \u2013 Science and Technology Publications, Lda\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017152557/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/317299391_High_Availability_and_Performance_of_Database_in_the_Cloud_-_Traditional_Master-slave_Replication_versus_Modern_Cluster-based_Solutions|archive-date=17 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MS-srv-perf-qa\">{{cite web|title=Server Hardware Performance Considerations|date=1 August 2018|access-date=17 October 2018\n|url=https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/administration/performance-tuning/hardware/|website=Microsoft IT Pro Center\n|first1=Phil|last1=Steel|first2=Liza|last2=Poggemeyer|first3=Corey|last3=Plett\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017175544/https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/administration/performance-tuning/hardware/\n|archive-date=17 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IBM-stor-cont-bk\">{{cite book|title=IBM System Storage Business Continuity: Part 2 Solutions Guide|chapter=Chapter 1. Three Business solution segments defined\n|first1=Charlotte|last1=Brooks|first2=Clem|last2=Leung|first3=Aslam|last3=Mirza|first4=Curtis|last4=Neal|first5=Yin Lei|last5=Qiu|first6=John|last6=Sing|first7=Francis TH|last7=Wong|first8=Ian R|last8=Wright|isbn=978-0738489728\n|publisher=IBM Redbooks|date=March 2007}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Crouch-CluDes\">{{cite web|title=Cluster design considerations|access-date=17 October 2017|website=Crouchbase\n|url=https://developer.couchbase.com/documentation/server/3.x/admin/Concepts/bp-clusterDesign.html\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017195247/https://developer.couchbase.com/documentation/server/3.x/admin/Concepts/bp-clusterDesign.html\n|url-status=live|archive-date=17 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Crouch-XDCR\">{{cite web|title=Cross Datacenter Replication (XDCR)|access-date=17 October 2017|website=Crouchbase\n|url=https://developer.couchbase.com/documentation/server/3.x/admin/XDCR/xdcr-intro.html\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017195516/https://developer.couchbase.com/documentation/server/3.x/admin/XDCR/xdcr-intro.html\n|url-status=live|archive-date=17 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Li-Manoharan\">{{cite conference|conference=2013 IEEE Pacific Rim Conference on Communications, Computers and Signal Processing (PACRIM)\n|title=A performance comparison of SQL and NoSQL databases|date=2013|first1=Yishan|last1=Li|first2=Sathiamoorthy|last2=Manoharan|page=15\n|doi=10.1109/PACRIM.2013.6625441|isbn=978-1-4799-1501-9|publisher=IEEE}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Database}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Very Large Database}}\n[[Category:Data management]]\n[[Category:Types of databases]]\n", "name_user": "Comp.arch", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Very_large_database"}
{"title_page": "Raila Odinga", "text_new": "{{short description|Kenyan politician}}\n{{Multiple issues\n|{{BLP sources|date=August 2017}}\n{{lead too long|date=August 2017}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name             = Raila Odinga\n| office1          = [[African Union High Representative for Infrastructure Development]]\n| 1blankname1      = [[Chairperson of the African Union Commission|Chair]]\n| 1namedata1       = [[Moussa Faki]]\n| term_start1      = 20 October 2018\n| term_end1        = \n| predecessor1     = [[Elisabeth Tankeu]] {{small|(2011){{Ref label|aab|b}}}}\n| office3          = [[Ministry of infrastructure|Minister of Roads, <br />Public Works and Housing]]\n| predecessor3     = William Cheruiyot Morogo\n| president3       = [[Mwai Kibaki]]\n| party            = [[Forum for the Restoration of Democracy]] {{small|(Before 1992)}}<br />[[Forum for the Restoration of Democracy \u2013 Kenya|Forum for the Restoration of Democracy-Kenya]] {{small|(1992\u20131994)}}<br />[[National Development Party (Kenya)|National Development Party]] {{small|(1994\u20132002)}}<br />[[Kenya African National Union]] {{small|(2000\u20132002)}}<br />[[Liberal Democratic Party (Kenya)|Liberal Democratic Party]] {{small|(2002\u20132005)}}<br />[[Orange Democratic Movement]] {{small|(2005\u2013present)}}\n| deputy2          = [[Musalia Mudavadi]]<br />[[Uhuru Kenyatta]]\n| office2          = 2nd [[Prime Minister of Kenya]]\n| predecessor2     = [[Jomo Kenyatta]] {{small|(1964){{Ref label|aaa|a}}}}\n| president2       = [[Mwai Kibaki]]\n| successor2       = ''Office abolished''\n| successor3       = [[Soita Shitanda]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=y|1945|1|7}}\n| birth_place      = [[Maseno]], [[Kenya Colony|Kenya]]\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| otherparty       = [[Coalition for Reforms and Democracy]] {{small|(2012\u20132017)}}<br />[[National Super Alliance]] {{small|(2017\u2013present)}}\n| spouse           = {{marriage|[[Ida Odinga]]|1973}}\n| children         = 4\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Nairobi]]<br />[[Leipzig University]]<br />[[Otto von Guericke University Magdeburg|Magdeburg University]]\n| website          = {{url|rao.co.ke|Official website}}<br />{{url|twitter.com/RailaOdinga|Official Twitter}}\n| term_start2      = 17 April 2008\n| term_end2        = 9 April 2013\n| term_start3      = 14 January 2003\n| term_end3        = 21 November 2005\n| office4          = [[Energy minister|Minister for Energy]]\n| president4       = [[Daniel arap Moi]]\n| term_start4      = 11 June 2001\n| term_end4        = 30 December 2002\n| predecessor4     = [[Francis Masakhalia]]\n| successor4       = [[Simeon Nyachae]]\n| office5          = [[Member of Parliament (Kenya)|Member of Parliament]]<br/>for [[Langata Constituency|Langata]] \n| term_start5      = 29 December 1992\n| term_end5        = 17 January 2013\n| predecessor5     = [[Philip Leakey]]\n| successor5       = Joash Olum\n| office6          = [[National Super Alliance]]<br /> People's President\n| term_start6      = 30 January 2018\n\n| term_end6        = \n| president6      = [[Uhuru Kenyatta]] \n| predecessor6     = Office created\n| successor6       = \n| relatives        = \n| image            = Raila A. Odinga.jpg\n| caption          = Odinga in 2017\n| footnotes        = <small> a. {{note|aaa}}[[Prime Minister of Kenya|Office of the Prime Minister]] vacant from 12 December 1964 to 17 April 2008.<br />b. {{note|aab}}Office vacant from 16 October 2011 to 20 October 2018; [[Elisabeth Tankeu]] served as the [[African Union]] Commissioner of Trade and Industry.</small>\n}}\n\n'''Raila Amolo Odinga ''' is a Kenyan politician who served as the [[Leader of the Opposition]] from 2013 - 14 Jan 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raila-odinga.com/biography |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218214305/http://www.raila-odinga.com/biography |archivedate=18 February 2013 |title=Biography: Raila Odinga |website=raila-odinga.com |accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Okwembah |first=David |date=1 March 2013 |title=Raila Odinga: Third time lucky in Kenya? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21587054 |newspaper=BBC News |accessdate=6 September 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228091914/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21587054 |archivedate=28 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was the Member of Parliament (MP) for [[Langata Constituency|Langata]] from 1992 to 2013. He served in the [[Cabinet of Kenya]] as Minister of Energy from 2001 to 2002, and as the Minister of Roads, Public Works and Housing from 2003 to 2005. Odinga was appointed [[African Union High Representative for Infrastructure Development|High Representative for Infrastructure Development]] at the [[African Union Commission]] in 2018.\n\nHe was the main opposition candidate in the [[2007 Kenyan presidential election|2007 presidential election]], running against incumbent [[Mwai Kibaki]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2000173013/how-mwai-kibaki-raila-odinga-power-sharing-deal-was-struck|title=How Mwai Kibaki, Raila Odinga power sharing deal was struck|first=Faith|last=Ronoh|website=standardmedia.co.ke|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020191701/https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2000173013/how-mwai-kibaki-raila-odinga-power-sharing-deal-was-struck|archivedate=20 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the subsequent [[2013 Kenyan presidential election|presidential election 5 years later]] he placed second against [[Uhuru Kenyatta]], garnering 5,340,546 votes, which represented 43.28% of the total votes cast.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/09/us-kenyan-elections-announcement-idUSBRE92717V20130309 Kenyatta was declared winner of Kenya's presidential vote] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513154224/http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/09/us-kenyan-elections-announcement-idUSBRE92717V20130309 |date=13 May 2013 }}. Reuters. Retrieved on 10 April 2013.</ref> He made another run for the presidency in August 2017 against Uhuru Kenyatta and lost<ref>[https://public.rts.iebc.or.ke/results/results.html IEBC Public Real-time Results Transmission Portal shows that Uhuru Kenyatta won] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808150433/https://public.rts.iebc.or.ke/results/results.html |date=8 August 2017 }} IEBC. Retrieved 17 September 2017.</ref> after the chairman of the electoral body declared Uhuru Kenyatta as the winner with 54% of the votes cast to Odinga's 43%.<ref>[http://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/Kenya-elections-results-president-uhuru-raila/1064-4053260-rko2c6/index.html Odinga's fourth loss in his attempts to be president of Kenya] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918021357/http://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/Kenya-elections-results-president-uhuru-raila/1064-4053260-rko2c6/index.html |date=18 September 2017 }}. Nation Media Group. Retrieved on 17 September 2017.</ref> This outcome was eventually annulled by the Supreme Court following findings that the election was marred by \"illegalities and irregularities\".\nA subsequent fresh election ordered by the Court was won by Uhuru Kenyatta when Odinga declined to participate citing inadequate reforms to enable a fair process in the repeat poll.\n\nSon of the first [[Vice President of Kenya]], [[Jaramogi Oginga Odinga]], he draws a large chunk of his support from various regions in Kenya, most notably the Coastal Region and his native former [[Nyanza Province]]. Odinga is commonly known as \"Baba\", coincidentally: he was an MP at the same time as his father between 1992 and 1994. Other nicknames that have been associated with the premier are such as \"Nyundo\" which is hammer in [[Kiswahili]], \"Tinga\" which means tractor in Kiswahili a symbol of his National Development Party, NDP, \"Agwambo\" meaning a man who is unpredictable and 'BABA' which means the political father.\n\nOdinga first ran as a presidential contender in the 1997 elections, coming third after President [[Daniel arap Moi]] of KANU and [[Mwai Kibaki]] of the [[Democratic Party (Kenya)|Democratic Party]]. He contested for President again in the December 2007 elections on an [[Orange Democratic Movement]] (ODM) ticket.\n\nIn readiness for that poll, on 1 September 2007, Odinga was picked as ODM's presidential nominee to face off with PNU's Kibaki in the current General Election. He managed to garner significant support in the 2007 general election. According to the electoral body at the time (the ECK), he swept the majority of the votes in [[Rift Valley Province|Rift Valley]] (Kenya's most populous area), [[Western Province (Kenya)|Western]], his native [[Nyanza Province|Nyanza]], and [[Coast Province|Coast]]. Kibaki on the other hand won majority votes in [[Nairobi County|Nairobi]] (the capital), [[North Eastern Province (Kenya)|North Eastern province]], [[Central Province (Kenya)|Central province]] and [[Eastern Province (Kenya)|Eastern province]], taking 4 provinces against Odinga's 4. Odinga's ODM party got 99 out of the 210 seats in the parliament, making it the single largest party in parliament.\n\nThe Kriegler report, commissioned to investigate the violent aftermath of the 2007 elections and alleged vote-rigging, stated that about 1.2 million dead voters existed in the voters register, raising serious doubts to the integrity of the election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/business/article/2000008868/in-kisumu-dead-voters-showed-up-at-the-polls |title=In Kisumu, dead voters 'showed up' at the polls |publisher=The Standard |date=2010-05-02 |accessdate=2017-09-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903080047/https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/business/article/2000008868/in-kisumu-dead-voters-showed-up-at-the-polls |archivedate=3 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 30 December 2007, the chairman of the Kenyan [[Electoral Commission of Kenya|election commission]] declared Odinga's opponent, incumbent president Kibaki, the winner of the presidential election by a slim margin of about 230,000 votes. Odinga disputed the results, alleging [[electoral fraud|fraud]] by the election commission. However he refused to follow due process of petitioning the courts, believing that the courts were under manipulation by Kibaki and so could not give a fair and impartial hearing.\n\nMost opinion polls had speculated that Odinga would defeat the president, though the margin kept narrowing as election day neared. Independent international observers have since stated that the poll was marred by irregularities in favor of both PNU and ODM, especially at the final vote tallying stages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationmedia.com/dailynation/nmgcontententry.asp?category_id=1&newsid=114851 |title=\"Observers criticize poll standards\" |accessdate=2008-01-20 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080121063149/http://www.nationmedia.com/dailynation/nmgcontententry.asp?category_id=1&newsid=114851 |archivedate=21 January 2008 |df=dmy-all }}, [[Daily Nation]], 18 January 2008.</ref> Many ODM supporters across the country [[civil unrest in Kenya (2007\u20132008)|rioted]] against the announced election results, triggering the worst national violence in post-independent Kenya.\n \nBesides his father, Odinga is identified as one of the leading forces behind the democratization process of Kenya, particularly during the repressive regime of President [[Daniel arap Moi]] (1978-2002) and the lead-up to the adoption of the new Constitution (2010) that re-affirmed many formerly neglected fundamental rights.\n\nIn 2017, Odinga [[2017 Kenyan general election|vied yet again for the presidency]], but lost to Uhuru Kenyatta. Odinga contested the election result in the Supreme Court, which nullified the results and called new elections as a result of electoral irregularities. Despite the Supreme Court ruling, Odinga announced on 10 October 2017 that he would withdraw from the second Presidential election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-41572128|title=Raila Odinga quits Kenya election re-run|date=10 October 2017|via=www.bbc.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021095749/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-41572128|archivedate=21 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRaila Odinga was born at the Anglican Church Missionary Society Hospital, in [[Maseno]], [[Kisumu District]], [[Nyanza Province]] on 7 January 1945 to [[Mary Ajuma Odinga]] and [[Jaramogi Oginga Odinga]]. His father served as the first [[Vice President of Kenya]] under President [[Jomo Kenyatta]].<ref name=usatoday>{{cite news|first=Heidi|last=Vogt|title=Kibaki, Odinga have a long history |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2008-02-28-4157951089_x.htm |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[USA Today]] |date=28 February 2008 |accessdate=9 August 2012}}</ref> He went to Kisumu Union Primary School, Maranda Primary and [[Maranda School]] where he dropped out in 1962. He spent the next two years at the [[Herder Institut]], a part of the [[Philology|philological faculty]] at the [[University of Leipzig]] in [[East Germany]].<ref name=\"bridge\">Daily Nation, 9 December 2007: [http://politics.nationmedia.com/inner.asp?fs=1&sid=520 aila Odinga: I\u2019m the bridge] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081002173329/http://politics.nationmedia.com/inner.asp?fs=1&sid=520 |date=2 October 2008 }}</ref> He received a scholarship that in 1965 sent him to the [[Magdeburg|Technical School, Magdeburg]] (now a part of [[Otto-von-Guericke University Magdeburg]]) in [[East Germany|the GDR]]. In 1970, he graduated with a diploma. While studying in [[East Berlin]] during the [[Cold War]], as a Kenyan he was able to visit [[West Berlin]] through the [[Checkpoint Charlie]]. When visiting West Berlin, he used to smuggle goods not available in East Berlin and bring them to his friends in East Berlin.<ref name=\"newsweek\">Newsweek Web Exclusive, 22 January 2008: [http://www.newsweek.com/id/97058 The Man Who Would Be President] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029210210/http://www.newsweek.com/id/97058 |date=29 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nHe returned to Kenya in 1970. In 1971 he established the ''Standard Processing Equipment Construction & Erection Ltd'' (later renamed ''East African Spectre''), a company manufacturing liquid petroleum gas cylinders. In 1974, he was appointed group standards manager of the [[Kenya Bureau of Standards]]. In 1978 he was promoted to its Deputy Director, a post he held until his 1982 detention.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}\n\n==Detention==\nIn an era of unrelenting human rights abuse by the Kenya government, Odinga was placed under [[house arrest]] for seven months after evidence seemed to implicate him along with his late father Oginga Odinga for collaborating with the plotters of a [[1982 Kenyan coup|failed coup attempt]] against President [[Daniel arap Moi]] in 1982. Hundreds of Kenyan civilians and thousands of rebel soldiers died in the coup. Several foreigners also lost their lives. Odinga was later charged with treason and detained without trial for six years.<ref>[[Human Rights Watch|Human rights Watch]], 1992: [https://www.hrw.org/reports/1992/WR92/AFW-03.htm Kenya: Human Rights Developments] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128133605/https://www.hrw.org/reports/1992/WR92/AFW-03.htm |date=28 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\nA biography released 14 years later in July 2006 apparently with Odinga's approval, indicated that Odinga was far more involved in the attempted coup than he had previously admitted. After its publication, some Members of Parliament in Kenya called for Odinga to be arrested and charged,<ref>The Standard, 17 July 2006: [http://allafrica.com/stories/200607171148.html \u201982 coup: Arrest Raila, say MPs] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016000149/http://allafrica.com/stories/200607171148.html |date=16 October 2012 }}</ref> but the [[statute of limitations]] had already passed and, since the information was contained in the biography did not amount to an open confession on his part.<ref>[[The Standard (Kenya)|The Standard]], 21 July 2006: [http://allafrica.com/stories/200607210225.html Why A-G won\u2019t charge Raila] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016000157/http://allafrica.com/stories/200607210225.html |date=16 October 2012 }}</ref> Among some of his most painful experiences was when his mother died in 1984 but the prison wardens took two months to inform him of her death.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}\n\nHe was released on 6 February 1988 only to be rearrested in September 1988 for his pro-democracy and human rights agitation at a time when the country continued to descend deep into the throes of poor governance.<ref>[[University of Pennsylvania]], African Studies Centre, East Africa Living Encyclopedia: [http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Hornet/irin_121397.html Kenya: IRIN Election Briefing, 12/13/97] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070316203333/http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Hornet/irin_121397.html |date=16 March 2007 }}</ref> and the despotism of single-party rule. [[multi-party system|multi-party democracy]] Kenya, was then, by law, a [[one-party state]]. His encounters with the authoritarian government generated an aura of intrigue about him and it was probably due to this his political followers, christened him \"Agwambo\", [[Luo language|Luo]] for \"The Mystery\" or \"Unpredictable\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2000230378/meet-woman-who-gave-raila-odinga-the-name-agwambo|title=Meet woman who gave Raila Odinga the name \u2018Agwambo\u2019|first=Kevine|last=Omollo|website=standardmedia.co.ke|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905055306/https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2000230378/meet-woman-who-gave-raila-odinga-the-name-agwambo|archivedate=5 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> or \"Jakom\", meaning Chairman.\n\nOdinga was released on 12 June 1989, only to be incarcerated again on 5 July 1990, together with [[Kenneth Matiba]], and former Nairobi Mayor [[Charles Rubia]], multiparty system and human rights crusaders .<ref>University of Pennsylvania, African Studies Centre, East Africa Living Encyclopedia: [http://www.africa.upenn.edu/NEH/khistory.htm Kenya \u2013 History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127162720/http://www.africa.upenn.edu/NEH/khistory.htm |date=27 November 2014 }}</ref> Odinga was finally released on 21 June 1991, and in October, he fled the country to Norway amid indications that the increasingly corrupt Kenyan government was attempting to assassinate him without success .<ref>The Standard, 16 July 2006: {{cite web |url=http://www.eastandard.net/archives/sunday/hm_news/news.php?articleid=1143955395&date=19%2F07%2F2006 |title=Day Raila fled disguised as priest |accessdate=2017-07-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080112082224/http://www.eastandard.net/archives/sunday/hm_news/news.php?articleid=1143955395&date=19%2F07%2F2006 |archivedate=12 January 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Multi-party politics==\nAt the time of Odinga's departure to Norway, the [[Forum for the Restoration of Democracy]] (FORD), a movement formed to agitate for the return of multi-party democracy to Kenya, was newly formed. In February 1992, Odinga returned to join FORD, then led by his father [[Jaramogi Oginga Odinga]]. He was elected Vice Chairman of the General Purposes Committee of the party. In the months running up to the 1992 General Election, FORD split into [[Ford-Kenya political party|Ford Kenya]], led by Odinga's father [[Jaramogi Oginga Odinga]], and [[Forum for the Restoration of Democracy-Asili|FORD-Asili]] led by [[Kenneth Matiba]]. Odinga became Ford-Kenya's Deputy Director of Elections. Odinga won the [[Langata Constituency]] parliamentary seat, previously held by [[Philip Leakey]] of KANU. Odinga became the second father of multi- party democracy in Kenya after Kenneth Matiba.<ref name=\"multiparty\">Center for Multiparty Democracy: [http://www.cmd.or.ke/images/Politics%20and%20Paliamenterians%20in%20Kenya.pdf Politics and Parliamentarians in Kenya 1944\u20132007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081028212845/http://www.cmd.or.ke/images/Politics%20and%20Paliamenterians%20in%20Kenya.pdf |date=28 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Jaramogi Oginga Odinga]] died in January 1994, and [[Michael Wamalwa Kijana]] succeeded him as FORD-Kenya chairman, Odinga challenged him for the party leadership. The elections were marred by controversy after which Odinga resigned from FORD-Kenya to join the [[National Development Party (Kenya)|National Development Party]] (NDP).\n\nIn his first bid for the presidency in the 1997 General Election, Odinga finished third after President Moi, the incumbent, and Democratic Party candidate [[Mwai Kibaki]]. He however retained his position as the Langata MP.<ref name=\"multiparty\"/>\n\nIn a surprise move, Odinga decided to support Moi, his arch-enemy, even entering into a political merger between his party, NDP, and Moi's much-hated [[Kenya African National Union|KANU]] party, which many Kenyans likened to the yoke of oppression. The merger was called New KANU. Previous admirers of Odinga now saw him as a sell-out to a cause he had once championed by closing ranks with a despot. He accepted a position in Moi's cabinet as Energy Minister, serving from June 2001 to 2002, during Moi's final term.\n\nIn the subsequent KANU elections held later that year, he was elected the party's Secretary General (replacing [[Joseph Kamotho]]).<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/200208060047.html Kenya: Saitoti, Raila And Kamotho Hold Breakfast Meeting] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020917071057/http://allafrica.com/stories/200208060047.html |date=17 September 2002 }}. allafrica.com. 6 August 2002</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Joe Khamisi|title=The Politics of Betrayal: Diary of a Kenyan Legislator|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=saw3XU7VaI4C+|date= 2011|publisher=Trafford Publishing|isbn=978-1-4269-8676-5|page=15}}</ref> It was apparent to many that Odinga hoped to ascend to the presidency through KANU and with Moi's support.\n\nIn 2002, much to the chagrin of Odinga and many other hopefuls in the party, Moi endorsed [[Uhuru Kenyatta]] \u2013 son of Kenya's first president [[Jomo Kenyatta]] but a relative newcomer in politics \u2013 to be his successor. Moi publicly asked Odinga and others to support Uhuru as well.<ref>BBC News, 16 September 2002: [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/2261085.stm Anti-Moi alliance emerging] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040717172624/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/2261085.stm |date=17 July 2004 }}</ref> This was taken as an affront by many of the party loyalists who felt they were being asked to make way for a newcomer who, unlike them, had done little to build the party. Odinga and other KANU members, including [[Kalonzo Musyoka]], [[George Saitoti]] and [[Joseph Kamotho]], opposed this step arguing that the then 38-year-old Uhuru was politically inexperienced and lacked the leadership qualities needed to govern. Moi stood his ground, maintaining that the country's leadership needed to pass to the younger generation.\n\nDissent ran through the party with some members openly disagreeing with Moi, despite his reputation as an autocrat. It was then that the Rainbow Movement was founded, comprising disgruntled KANU members who exited KANU. The exodus, led by Odinga, saw most big names fleeing the party. Moi was left with his handpicked successor almost alone with a party reduced to an empty shell with poor electoral prospects. The Rainbow Movement went on to join the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Kenya)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (LDP), which later teamed up with opposition Mwai Kibaki's [[National Alliance Party of Kenya]] (NAK), a coalition of several other parties, to form the [[National Rainbow Coalition]] ([[National Rainbow Coalition|NARC]]).\n\nAmid fears that this opposition \"super alliance\", would fail to unite and rally behind a common candidate as in previous occasions thus easily hand victory to the government, Odinga declared \"''Kibaki tosha''\", Swahili for \"Kibaki is sufficient\", an endorsement of a Kibaki ticket. This resolved the matter of candidacy and Narc went on to defeat Moi's protege, Uhuru Kenyatta. The opposition won a landslide 67% of the vote, dealing a humiliating blow to Moi. Odinga led the campaign for Kibaki throughout the country while Kibaki was bedridden and incapacitated following an accident in which he sustained injuries.\n\n==Dissent from within==\n[[File:Gordon Brown Raila Odinga.JPG|thumb|Odinga with [[Gordon Brown]] at [[Kibera]]]]\nOn assuming office, President Kibaki did not appoint Odinga as Prime Minister in the new government, contrary to a pre-election MOU. (Kenya's constitution had no provision for Prime minister yet); neither did he give LDP (Odinga's faction) half of the cabinet positions as per the MOU. He instead sought to entrench and increase his own NAK's side in cabinet, even appointing MPs from the opposition parties (KANU and FORD people) to the cabinet.<ref>BBC News, 30 September 2003: [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3356431.stm Uproar over Kenya leader's decree] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040720215552/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3356431.stm |date=20 July 2004 }}</ref>\n\nThe perceived \"betrayal\" started a simmering disquiet which in time led to an open rebellion and a split within the cabinet. A key point of disagreement was a proposed new constitution for the country, which was a major campaign issue that had united Kibaki's NAK and Odinga's LDP in the campaign. This constitution included provisions to trim presidential powers to rein in what was seen as an autocratic presidency, a feature of both the Moi and first president Jomo Kenyatta's regimes which had led to a lot of power abuse and an unaccountable leadership.\n\nOnce in power however, Kibaki's government instituted a Constitutional Committee which turned around and submitted a draft constitution that was perceived to consolidate presidential powers and weaken regional governments, contrary to the pre-election draft.\n\nOdinga opposed this and went on to campaign with his LDP cabinet colleagues on the referendum 'No' side, opposing the President and his lieutenants in a bruising countrywide campaign. When the document was put to a [[2005 Kenyan constitutional referendum|referendum]] on 21 November 2005, the government lost by a 57% to 43% margin. Embarrassingly for Kibaki, out of 8 provinces, only one ( Central Province where his tribe the Kikuyu are dominant) voted \"yes\" for the document, isolating his own tribe from the rest of Kenya and exposing his campaign as ethnic- based.\n\nA shell-shocked and disappointed President Kibaki sacked the entire cabinet on 23 November 2005. When it was reconstituted two weeks later, Odinga and the entire LDP group were left out.\n\nThis led to the formation of a new opposition outfit, the Orange Democratic Movement (ODM) \u2013 an Orange was the symbol for the \"No\" vote in the constitutional referendum.\n\nIn January 2006, Odinga was reported to have told police that he believed his life was in danger, having received assassination threats.<ref>BBC News, 10 January 2006: [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/4599834.stm Kenyan opponent 'fears for life'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060113105542/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/4599834.stm |date=13 January 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==2007 presidential election==\nOn 12 July 2007, with Kibaki's reelection bid drawing close, Odinga alleged that the government was withholding [[Identity document|identity cards]] from voters in opposition strongholds with intention to skew the election in favour of Kibaki. He also claimed that the intended creation of 30 new constituencies was a means by the government to fraudulently engineer victory in the [[2007 Kenyan parliamentary election|December 2007 parliamentary election]].<ref>David Schlesinger and Barry Moody, [http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=87&art_id=nw20070713104933431C315734 \"Presidential hopeful doubts free, fair polls\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060615021453/http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1 |date=15 June 2006 }}, Reuters (''IOL''), 13 July 2007.</ref>\n\n[[File:Raila and the media.jpg|thumb|Odinga addressing the Kenyan media during the [[2007\u201308 Kenyan crisis]]]]\nIn August 2007, the Odinga's own Orange Democratic Movement-Kenya suffered a setback when it split into two, with Odinga becoming head of the Orange Democratic Movement (ODM) while the other faction, the ODM-K, was headed by [[Kalonzo Musyoka]] who parted ways with Odinga.<ref>Peter Clottey, [http://www.voanews.com/english/Africa/2007-08-16-voa1.cfm \"Kenya's Opposition Split Brightens Kibaki's Second Term Bid\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070817225414/http://www.voanews.com/english/Africa/2007-08-16-voa1.cfm |date=17 August 2007 }}, [[Voice of America|VOA News]], 16 August 2007.</ref>\n\nOn 1 September 2007, the ODM elected Odinga as its presidential candidate in a National Delegates Conference held at the [[Moi International Sports Centre]] in Nairobi. Odinga received 2,656 votes; the only other candidates who received significant numbers of votes were [[Musalia Mudavadi]] with 391 and [[William Ruto]] with 368. Earlier, [[Najib Balala]] had withdrawn his candidature and endorsed Odinga.<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/200709010028.html \"Kenya: It's Raila for President\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926231155/http://allafrica.com/stories/200709010028.html |date=26 September 2007 }}, ''The Standard'', 1 September 2007.</ref> The defeated candidates expressed their support for Odinga afterward, and Mudavadi was named as his [[running mate]].<ref>Maina Muiruri, [http://www.eastandard.net/InsidePage.php?id=1143973907 \"ODM \u2018pentagon\u2019 promises to keep the team intact\"]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''The Standard'' (Kenya), 2 September 2007.</ref>\n\nOdinga then launched his [[Political campaign|presidential campaign]] in [[Uhuru Park]] in Nairobi on 6 October 2007.\n\nOdinga's bid for the presidency however failed when after the 27 December [[2007 Kenyan presidential election|presidential election]], the Electoral Commission declared Kibaki the winner on 30 December 2007, placing him ahead of Odinga by about 232,000 votes. [[Jeffrey Sachs]] (Professor of Economics and Director of [[the Earth Institute]] at [[Columbia University]], and Special Advisor to former [[United Nations Secretary-General|UN Secretary General]]) faulted the United States' approach to the post-election crisis and recommended an independent recount of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/?page=2008%5C01%5C25%5Cstory_25-1-2008_pg3_4 |title=Leading News Resource of Pakistan |publisher=Daily Times |date=25 January 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606183629/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/?page=2008%5C01%5C25%5Cstory_25-1-2008_pg3_4 |archivedate=6 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Raila Amolo Odinga with Obamas.jpg|left|thumb|President [[Barack Obama]] and First Lady [[Michelle Obama]] of the United States pose for a photo during a reception at the Metropolitan Museum in New York with Raila Odinga, [[Prime Minister of Kenya|Prime Minister of the Republic of Kenya]], and his wife, Mrs. [[Ida Odinga]]]]\nOdinga and his ODM leaders rallied against the decision with James Orengo and Prof. Nyong'o calling for mass action. Later violence broke out in the country.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/12/31/2129125.htm?section=world \"Kibaki re-elected Kenyan president: official results\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090823052314/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/12/31/2129125.htm?section=world |date=23 August 2009 }}, AFP (abc.net.au), 31 December 2007.</ref>\nThe government's response was heavy-handed as it deployed police and paramilitary units to counter public protests.\n\nFollowing two months of unrest, which led to the death of about 1000 people and displacement of about 250, 000, a deal between Odinga and Kibaki, which provided for power-sharing and the creation of the post of Prime Minister, was signed in February 2008; it was brokered by former UN Secretary General [[Kofi Annan]]. Odinga was sworn in as Prime Minister, along with the power-sharing Cabinet, on 17 April 2008. The post of Prime Minister was last held by [[Jomo Kenyatta]] between 1963 and 1964 following independence. Odinga is thus the second person in Kenya's history to hold the position.<ref>Eric Ombok, [https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=abAJ_3lpr8WA&refer=home \"Kenya's Raila Odinga Sworn in as Prime Minister, Ending Crisis\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613163056/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |date=13 June 2010 }}, Bloomberg.com, 17 April 2008.</ref>\n\n[[File:Prime Minister of Kenya (7752141076).jpg|left|thumb|[[British Foreign Secretary]] [[William Hague]] meeting Odinga, then Prime Minister of Kenya, in London, 10 August 2012]]\n\n==2013 presidential election==\n[[File:Raila Odinga speaking at visit to Peace Corps.jpg|thumb|Odinga speaking at a visit to Peace Corps]]\n\nThe next presidential election in which Odinga was to run was the 2013 March poll, involving Kibaki's handover of power. Uncertainty loomed over Odinga's main rivals, Uhuru Kenyatta and William Ruto, who had both been indicted by the [[International Criminal Court|ICC]] of the Hague for their alleged role in the 2007 election violence. \nDespite their pending case, the duo had been nominated by the Jubilee party with Uhuru as presidential candidate and Ruto as running mate. \nMany felt they were unfit to run for office before clearing their names from such serious crimes while others felt that their opponents were trying to unfairly exploit the situation by eliminating them from the race and pave the way for their easy victory.\n\nA Synovate survey released in October 2012 found Odinga to enjoy a leading 45 percent approval rate against Uhuru and Ruto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201104170037.html |title=allAfrica.com: Kenya: Raila's Ratings Fall But Still Ahead of the Pack |publisher=allAfrica |date=15 April 2010 |accessdate=15 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nOdinga's party, Orange Democratic Movement (ODM) joined Kalonzo Musyoka's Wiper Party and Moses Wetangula's Ford Kenya (FK) in a CORD coalition (Coalition for Reforms and Democracy) for the presidential race with Odinga as the presidential candidate and Kalonzo as his running mate to face Jubilee's coalition ( [[Uhuru Kenyatta]]'s (The National Alliance \u2013 TNA), [[William Ruto]]'s (United Republican Party \u2013 URP), [[Charity Ngilu]]'s (National Rainbow Coalition \u2013 NARC) and [[Najib Balala]]'s (Republican Congress \u2013 RC)).\n\nA number of western countries were not in favour of the Uhuru and Ruto candidacy in view of their pending ICC cases and association with crimes against humanity. Former UN Secretary General Koffi Annan voiced his reservations, as did former US Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs [[Johnnie Carson]] who cautioned against the election of Uhuru Kenyatta and William Ruto. He was notably quoted as saying that \"Choices have consequences, \" referring to the fate of US-Kenyan relations, with a Uhuru administration.\n\n[[File:Opening Plenary - World Economic Forum on Africa 2008.jpg|left|thumb|Odinga, Prime Minister of Kenya, with, from left, [[Pierre Nkurunziza]], [[President of Burundi]], [[Bingu Wa Mutharika]], [[President of Malawi]], [[Thabo Mbeki]], [[President of South Africa]], [[Klaus Schwab]], Founder and Executive Chairman, [[World Economic Forum]], and [[John Agyekum Kufuor]], [[President of Ghana]], during the Opening Plenary of the World Economic Forum on Africa 2008 in [[Cape Town]], South Africa, 4 June 2008]]\n\nOdinga ran for President in the elections held on 4 March 2013 and garnered 5,340,546 votes (43.70%) out of the 12,221,053 valid votes cast. The winner, Uhuru Kenyatta garnered 6,173,433 votes (50.51%). As this was above the 50% plus 1 vote threshold, Uhuru won it on the first round without requiring a run-off between the top two candidates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iebc.or.ke/index.php/resources/downloads/item/summary-of-2013-presidential-results-declared-on-932013?category_id=26 |title=SUMMARY OF 2013 PRESIDENTIAL RESULTS DECLARED ON 9/3/2013 |publisher=IEBC |date=3 April 2013 |accessdate=3 April 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315145243/http://www.iebc.or.ke/index.php/resources/downloads/item/summary-of-2013-presidential-results-declared-on-932013?category_id=26 |archivedate=15 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission (IEBC) therefore officially declared Uhuru Kenyatta the president elect on Saturday 9 March at 2:44pm. Uhuru was set to take office as Kenya's 4th president.\n\nHowever, in a press conference shortly after the results were announced, Odinga said that the election had been marred by massive failures of the Biometric Voter Registration(BVR) kits, EVID (electronic voter identification or \"Pollbooks\"), RTS (results transmission system or \"tallying system\") and the RPS (results presentation or \"transmissions system\"). He claimed that the manual tallying was suspect leaving him no choice but to [[The Kenya Presidential Election Petition 2013]] contest the result in Kenya's highest court, The Supreme Court.\n\nIn anticipation of the legal challenge, Odinga and his lawyers George Oraro, Mutula Kilonzo, and James Orengo, secretly instructed Raj Pal Senna,<ref>[http://rajpalsenna.com/index/ Landing Page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102062042/http://rajpalsenna.com/index/ |date=2 November 2014 }}. Raj Pal Senna (25 April 2014). Retrieved on 21 April 2015.</ref> a Management Consultant from Barcelona to carry out a forensic investigation of the technology used in the Kenyan General Election 2013, during which the IEBC made claims on TV and media that there were \"technological challenges\", that servers overloaded and that database crashed.<ref>[http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/print/2000083919/the-raila-supreme-court-evidence Standard Digital News \u2013 Kenya : Breaking News, Latest, Business, Jobs, Football, Travel, Tourism, Elections, National, Nairobi, County, East Africa, Media] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102041411/http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/print/2000083919/the-raila-supreme-court-evidence |date=2 November 2014 }}. Standardmedia.co.ke (15 April 2015). Retrieved on 21 April 2015.</ref><ref>[https://www.ktnkenya.tv/?articleID=2000083919&story_title=what-raila-failed-to-tell-in-petition-against-uhuru&pageNo=2 Standard Digital News \u2013 Kenya : What Raila failed to tell in petition against Uhuru] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102035800/https://www.ktnkenya.tv/?articleID=2000083919&story_title=what-raila-failed-to-tell-in-petition-against-uhuru&pageNo=2 |date=2 November 2014 }}. Ktnkenya.tv. Retrieved on 21 April 2015.</ref>\n\nKenya's chief justice Dr. [[Willy Mutunga]] announced on Monday, 11 March that the Supreme Court was fully formed and ready to deliver its judgements within 14 days as stipulated by the constitution of Kenya.\n\nDuring the Petition hearing, Chief Justice Willy Mutunga made a finding rejecting second affidavit of Odinga which comprised 900 pages, on the basis that it amounted to \"new evidence\" which is not permitted under the Constitution. Subsequently, The Supreme Court issued a ruling dismissing the petition on 30 March 2013. The Supreme Court while declaring Uhuru the next President also declared that the [[Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission|IEBC]] should not have included the invalid/spoilt votes in the calculation of the final figures and percentages.\nChief Justice Willy Mutunga also directed that the EACC (Ethics and Anti Corruption Commission) and the DPP (Director of Public Prosecutions) carry out a criminal investigation of the IEBC in relation to the BVR, EVID, RTS and RPS.<ref name=\"businessdailyafrica.com\">[http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Kenya-poll-officials-IT-vendors-face-probe-over-glitches-/-/539546/1750444/-/bax88r/-/index.html IEBC officials may be prosecuted over gadget failure \u2013 Politics and policy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102070134/http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Kenya-poll-officials-IT-vendors-face-probe-over-glitches-/-/539546/1750444/-/bax88r/-/index.html |date=2 November 2014 }}. businessdailyafrica.com (16 April 2013). Retrieved on 21 April 2015.</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Supreme Court of Kenya|supreme court]] [[The Kenya Presidential Election Petition 2013|dismissed his petition]] Odinga flew to South Africa to avoid attending the Inauguration of Uhuru Kenyatta, held on 9 April 2013 at Moi Sports Complex at Kasarani, Nairobi. The swearing ceremony marked the end of his premiership.\n\nIn an important development, the full investigation findings were published as the [[OpCo Report]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150711110418/http://kenya-legal.com/main/efiles/1/15/op-co-report-election-4-mar-2013 OpCo Report: Election 4 Mar 2013]. kenya-legal.com (24 January 2014)</ref> on the website www.kenya-legal.com and inspired the documentary \"50+1 \u2013 The Inside Story\"<ref>[http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/ktn/video/watch/2000077350/-part-one-the-inside-story-50-1-what-really-happened-during-the-2013-elections Standard Digital News \u2013 KTN : KTN Video | Part One: The Inside Story 50+1 (What really happened during the 2013 elections)]. Standardmedia.co.ke. (25 April 2014).</ref> by KTN journalists John Namu and Mohammed Ali.\n\nThis documentary examines the history of election fraud and the history of corruption in the Judiciary, and in which Odinga claims that it can not be ruled out that it was a deliberate act or omission by the Court not to subject the technical evidence to scrutiny because the outcome would invalidate the entire election process and discredit the IEBC.\n\n==2017 presidential elections==\n===Claims of election rigging===\nOdinga, through his lawyer James Orengo, Otiende Amollo and Clifford Ochieng claimed that forces associated with his main competitor Uhuru Kenyatta had hacked into the IEBC (Kenya's electoral body) server and tampered with its database. He stated that the results that were being transmitted by IEBC were false because they had been manipulated via a computer algorithm designed to maintain an 11% gap between him and Uhuru's votes. As such, he proved the votes were not real votes cast by human voters but the outcome of a computer generated formula producing artificial values. This intrusion into IEBC's system, he further said, affected not just the presidential results but the entire election, including the votes cast for MPs, Senators, Governors and Women Representatives. He called the alleged intrusion \"the biggest vote theft in Kenya\u2019s history.\" Later while vote tallying was still in progress and the country was awaiting announcement of the final results, Odinga revealed that his team had received information from a confidential source in IEBC indicating that results from its server showed him leading with an unassailable 8 million votes over Uhuru's 7 million votes. Based on this, he demanded he be declared the 5th [[President of Kenya]].\n\nThe IEBC however rejected Odinga's contention, saying the winner could not be announced before the tallying was complete and also being an independent body it could not be compelled by one of the candidates to announce the results.\n\nThe IEBC finally announced the results declaring Uhuru the winner with 8.2 million votes against Odinga's 6.7 million. The results showed massive losses for NASA, with Jubilee invading traditional NASA strongholds. NASA refused to recognize the results.\n\nShortly after Uhuru's declared victory, violence was reported in some parts of the country which are opposition strongholds. However the violence was not of the scale witnessed in the 2007 election aftermath and broke out only sporadically. Both Odinga and President Kenyatta called for public calm.\n\n===Annulment of the presidential election===\nAfter initially declining to take his case to court on the grounds that the court had previously made an unfavourable judgment against him, Odinga reconsidered and lodged a petition.\n\nAfter 2 days of hearing, the judges in a majority 4\u20132 decision returned a verdict on 1 September annulling the presidential results and ordered a new election to be held within 60 days. The court decision, read by Chief Justice David Maraga and widely viewed as unprecedented both in Africa and globally held that the IEBC failed to conduct the election in the manner provided by the Constitution and so could not stand.<ref>{{cite web|last1=FREYTAS-TAMURA|first1=KIMIKO|title=Kenya Supreme Court Nullifies Presidential Election|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/01/world/africa/kenya-election-kenyatta-odinga.html?_r=0|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901210458/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/01/world/africa/kenya-election-kenyatta-odinga.html?_r=0|archivedate=1 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDespite the Supreme Court ruling, Odinga announced his withdrawal from the Presidential election, scheduled for 26 October,<ref name=\"veconomist\">{{cite news|title=Raila Odinga takes a gamble by threatening to boycott Kenya\u2019s election|url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21730121-first-poll-was-annulled-second-may-be-violently-disrupted-raila-odinga|work=[[The Economist]]|date=11 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012061227/https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21730121-first-poll-was-annulled-second-may-be-violently-disrupted-raila-odinga|archivedate=12 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> on 10 October.<ref name=odingwithd>http://ntv.co.ug/news/international/10/oct/2017/i-will-not-be-forced-participate-election-re-run-says-raila-odinga#sthash.Cjs9fhpG.dpbs {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010142116/http://www.ntv.co.ug/news/international/10/oct/2017/i-will-not-be-forced-participate-election-re-run-says-raila-odinga |date=10 October 2017 }}</ref> The reason for his withdrawal was his belief that the election would again not be free or fair, since no electoral process reforms had been made since the annulment of the last election,<ref name=\"veconomist\" /> as well as various defections which occurred from his coalition.<ref name=odingwithd />\n\nIEBC later stated that Odinga had not officially withdrawn from the race for presidency and his would still appear on the ballot on 26 October among other candidates who contested in the 8 August General Elections.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://nairobinews.nation.co.ke/news/iebc-raila-not-withdrawn-presidential-race/|title=IEBC: Raila has not withdrawn from presidential race - Nairobi News|date=2017-10-11|work=Nairobi News|access-date=2017-10-12|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012203220/http://nairobinews.nation.co.ke/news/iebc-raila-not-withdrawn-presidential-race/|archivedate=12 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThis resulted to violent uproar in various parts of the country some few days before and after the repeat polls especially in the NASA dominated zones. Alleged police brutality was reported as independent medic research organization (IMLU) cited 39 deaths and high assault cases\n\n===Swearing in of People's President, and reconciliation===\nOn 30 January, Odinga staged a swearing in ceremony in Nairobi where he named himself 'People's President. Following this ceremony TV stations across Kenya were taken off air. A month and a half later, on 9 March, Odinga and president Uhuru Kenyatta made a joint televised appearance in which they referred to each other as 'brothers,' and agreed to put aside political differences to allow Kenya to move forward.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/30/world/africa/raila-odinga-kenya.html|title=Kenyans Name a \u2018People\u2019s President,\u2019 and TV Broadcasts Are Cut|date=30 January 2018|via=NYTimes.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180202215536/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/30/world/africa/raila-odinga-kenya.html|archivedate=2 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-42905290|title=Kenya TV off air despite court ruling|date=1 February 2018|via=www.bbc.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201111606/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-42905290|archivedate=1 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-43345217 |title=Kenya's Uhuru Kenyatta and Raila Odinga now 'brothers' |date=9 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018 |website=bbc.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312012627/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-43345217 |archivedate=12 March 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== The Building Bridges Initiative ==\nFollowing the March 2018 truce between Mr. Odinga and President Kenyatta, the two commissioned a joint task force that would collect views from Kenyans and report their findings. After touring the country and holding consultative sessions, the team compiled and submitted the report to President Kenyatta at State House Nairobi on 26 November 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001350941/president-uhuru-receives-bbi-report|title=President Uhuru receives BBI report|last=Ogila|first=Japheth|website=The Standard|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> which was followed by a public launch at the Bomas of Kenya the following day.<ref>{{Citation|title=Kenya unites behind BBI at Bomas - VIDEO|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/Delegates-arrive-at-Bomas-of-Kenya-for-BBI-report-launch/1064-5364226-5ec7tg/index.html|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> The efforts by President Kenyatta and Mr. Odinga to bring peace and cohesion in the country were applauded by several leaders locally and internationally with the duo being invited to the [[International Lunch]] in Washington DC, USA in February 2020 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Peace-deal-earns-Uhuru-and-Raila-US-invite/1056-5431876-c5m9da/index.html|title=Peace deal earns Uhuru and Raila US invite|website=Daily Nation|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n===Economics===\nOginga's political ideology can be loosely styled as social democracy, more closely aligned with American left wing politics. His position was once in favour of a parliamentary system as seen when he initially backed a Constitution giving executive powers to a Prime Minister but he subsequently changed to a presidential system with a devolved power structure, which is reflected in Kenya's current constitution.\n\nOdinga is seen as the main force behind devolution now enshrined in Kenya's constitution as an essential part of Kenya's governance system. This was inspired by a feeling that all successive governments under the centralized power structure had consistently abused that power to favour certain areas along political or ethnic lines while denying many regions access to resources and development because of their ethnicity or perceived disloyalty. Devolution aimed to address this and guarantee regions their fair share of resources regardless of their political affiliation or ethnicity.\n\nDue to an economic downturn and extreme drought, Odinga has called for the suspension of taxes on fuels and certain foods that disproportionately impact the poor.\n<ref>Kenya Broadcasting Corporation, 1 June 2011: [http://www.kbc.co.ke/news.asp?nid=70521 Principles Unite in Addressing High Cost of Living] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321070428/http://www.kbc.co.ke/news.asp?nid=70521 |date=21 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOdinga has supported an element of state welfare in the form of cash-transfer programs to low-income people. This is currently implemented but in a limited way to poor, elderly people.\n\n[[File:Foreign Office Minister Henry Bellingham meeting Kenyan Prime Minister Raila Odinga in London, 7 July 2011. (5911639399).jpg|left|thumb|British Foreign Office Minister [[Henry Bellingham (Norfolk MP)|Henry Bellingham]] meeting Odinga in [[London]], 7 July 2011]]\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Raila and Ida Odinga.jpg|thumb|right|Odinga and his wife [[Ida Odinga|Ida]] at a political rally]]\nBaptised as an Anglican Christian in the Church Missionary Society (CMS) in his childhood,<ref>The Standard, 5 November 2007: [http://allafrica.com/stories/200711050379.html ODM promises smooth transition if it wins] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012022613/http://allafrica.com/stories/200711050379.html |date=12 October 2012 }}</ref> Odinga later became a [[Born-Again]] [[Christians|Christian]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/8033376.stm |title='Doomsday' man baptises Kenya PM |publisher=BBC News |date=5 May 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090509213347/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/8033376.stm |archivedate=9 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and is a communicant member of All saints' Cathedral in Nairobi.\n\nOdinga is married to [[Ida Odinga]] (Ida Anyango Oyoo). They live in Karen, Nairobi and have a second home at central Farm, in [[Siaya County]]. The couple have four children: Fidel (1973\u20132015),<ref>{{Cite news\n |last        = Leftie, Peter, Zaddock Angira, Njoki Chege and Stella Cherono\n |title       = Raila family in mourning as eldest son found dead in bed after night partying \u2013 News \u2013 nation.co.ke\n |work        = Daily Nation, nation.co.ke\n |accessdate  = 8 January 2015\n |date        = 4 January 2014\n |url         = http://www.nation.co.ke/news/Mystery-as-Raila-son-found-dead-in-his-bed-/-/1056/2578692/-/6m8fbl/-/index.html\n |url-status  = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20150107171446/http://www.nation.co.ke/news/Mystery-as-Raila-son-found-dead-in-his-bed-/-/1056/2578692/-/6m8fbl/-/index.html\n |archivedate = 7 January 2015\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Rosemary (born 1977), Raila Jr. (born 1979) and Winnie (born 1990). Fidel was named after [[Fidel Castro]]<ref name=\"price\">Daily Nation, 2 June 2001 {{cite web |url=http://www.nationaudio.com/News/DailyNation/02062001/Features/Feature.html |title=The Price of being Raila Odinga's wife |accessdate=2008-01-01 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080128160832/http://www.nationaudio.com/News/DailyNation/02062001/Features/Feature.html |archivedate=28 January 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Winnie after [[Winnie Mandela]]. Winnie is currently studying Communication and International Area Studies as a double major student at [[Drexel University]] in [[Philadelphia]].<ref name=\"price\"/>\n\nIn an interview with [[BBC News]] in January 2008, Odinga asserted that he was the first cousin of [[United States|U.S.]] president [[Barack Obama]] through Obama's father.<ref name=\"Obama\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7176683.stm Odinga says Obama is his cousin] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316225109/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7176683.stm |date=16 March 2008 }}, [[BBC News]], 1/8/08.</ref> However, Barack Obama's paternal uncle denied any direct relation to Odinga, stating \"Odinga's mother came from this area, so it is normal for us to talk about cousins. But he is not a blood relative.\"<ref name=\"Said Obama\">[http://africa.reuters.com/wire/news/usnL08727241.html Some Kenyans forget crisis to root for Obama] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014112941/http://africa.reuters.com/wire/news/usnL08727241.html |date=14 October 2008 }}, [[Reuters]], 1/8/08.</ref>\n\nOdinga briefly played soccer for [[Luo Union]] (now [[Gor Mahia F.C.|Gor Mahia]]) as a [[Midfielder (association football)|midfielder]].<ref name=\"price\"/>\n\nOdinga was appointed by the [[African Union]] to mediate the [[2010-2011 Ivorian crisis]], which involved [[Alassane Ouattara]] and [[Laurent Gbagbo]].\nOdinga wrote \"Flame of Freedom\" a 1040 paged [[autobiography]] which talks about his life from childhood. It was launched on 6 October 2013 in [[Kenya]] and subsequently in United States on 15 October 2013. He was accompanied by a section of Kenyan county governors.\n\n==Controversy==\nDuring his premiership, Odinga appointed [[Miguna Miguna]] as his advisor on coalition affairs, whom he later suspended in August 2011,<ref>Daily Nation, 4 August 2011, [http://www.nation.co.ke/News/politics/Raila+kicks+out+key+aide/-/1064/1213684/-/irw5r6z/-/index.html Raila kick out Key aid] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518053425/http://www.nation.co.ke/News/politics/Raila+kicks+out+key+aide/-/1064/1213684/-/irw5r6z/-/index.html |date=18 May 2014 }}.</ref> citing \"gross misconduct\". The ''[[Daily Nation]]'' quoted his reason for suspension as being \"accused of misrepresenting the office of the Prime Minister, possibly a reference to his having aired strong views which may have embarrassed the PM.\" Miguna Miguna latter published controversial books about his working relationship with Odinga.\n\nHis suspension came at a time when the electoral body, the [[Interim Independent Electoral Commission of Kenya|IIEC]], was in an uproar and unsettled by anonymously authored complaints which the commissioners characterise as a hate campaign but which raise troubling questions on corruption and nepotism. Later Miguna, after suspension, issued a statement that said he \"was instructed to write my article on the IIEC chairman and the position he had taken with respect to the party's decision to kick out rebellious [[Member of Parliament|MP]]s and Councillors.\" He later denied, according to the ''[[Nairobi Star]]''.<ref>Nairobi Star. 13 August 2011. In a twist of events however there are rumours that he will stand down and let one of the CORD principals Mr. Wetangula vie for presidency and back the Jubilee Party to be launched in September 2016. Odinga was the leader of the opposition who let hundreds of people get killed for no cause. [http://www.the-star.co.ke/national/national/35896-miguna-slams-raila Miguna Slam Raila] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404163957/http://www.the-star.co.ke/national/national/35896-miguna-slams-raila |date=4 April 2012 }}.</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, in a leaked video recording, a voice of one Moses Wetangula, the then Senator of Bungoma, appeared to implicate Odinga in a gold deal gone sour, a deal in which billions of dollars were lost by the UAE king https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/news/Wetangula-says-fake-gold-scam/539546-5136278-sxisrr/index.html\n\n==Honours and awards==\n===Honorary degrees===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! University !! Country !! Honour !! style=\"width:60px;\"|Year \n|-\n| [[University of Nairobi]] || {{flag|Kenya}} || [[Doctor of Laws]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"|2008<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uonbi.ac.ke/sites/default/files/Citation%20on%20Raila.pdf |title=Citation |format=PDF |date=2008 |publisher=University of Nairobi |accessdate=12 November 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812083559/http://www.uonbi.ac.ke/sites/default/files/Citation%20on%20Raila.pdf |archivedate=12 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Florida A&M University]] || {{flag|United States}} || Honorary degree || style=\"text-align:center;\"|2012<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kenyacentral.com/feed/http://www.kenyacentral.com/general/30017-applause-as-%E2%80%98dr-odinga%E2%80%99-returns.txt |title=Kenya Online: Applause as \u2018Dr Odinga\u2019 returns |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=2012 |website=kenyacentral.com |publisher= |accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Limkokwing University of Creative Technology]] || {{flag|Malaysia}} || Doctorate of Leadership in Social Development || style=\"text-align:center;\"|2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.limkokwing.net/malaysia/community/recognized_leadership/rt._hon._raila_amolo_odinga|title=Recognized_leadership: Rt. Hon. Raila Amolo Odinga|date=2012|publisher=Limkokwing University|accessdate=12 November 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112033833/http://www.limkokwing.net/malaysia/community/recognized_leadership/rt._hon._raila_amolo_odinga|archivedate=12 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Luo people of Kenya and Tanzania]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Badejo|first=Babafemi A.|year=2006 |title=Raila Odinga: An Enigma in Kenyan Politics |location=Lagos; Nairobi|publisher= Yintab Books |isbn=9783720880}}\n*{{cite book |last=Odinga|first=Raila|last2=Elderkin|first2=Sarah |year=2013 |title=The Flame of Freedom |location=Nairobi, Kenya |publisher=Mountain Top Publishers and Worldreader |isbn=9966050582}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links | wikt=no |q=no| b=no | n=no |s=no | v=no | voy=no | species=no |d=Q57657| display=Raila Odinga}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21587054 Profile on BBC]\n*[http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2013/02/201322216228573605.html Profile on Aljazeera]\n*[http://softkenya.com/railaodinga/ Raila Odinga \u2013 Profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n|-\n{{s-vac|last=[[Jomo Kenyatta]]|reason = Office suspended}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Kenya]]|years=2008\u20132013}}\n{{s-non|reason=Position abolished}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Uhuru Kenyatta]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-par|ke}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = Member of the National Assembly of Kenya<br /> for [[Langata Constituency|Langata]]\n| before = [[Philip Leakey]]\n| after  = Joash Olum\n| years  = 1992\u20132013\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Raila Odinga}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Articles related to Raila Odinga\n|list1=\n{{KenyaPMs}}\n{{2007 presidential candidates, Kenya}}\n{{2013 presidential candidates, Kenya}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odinga, Raila}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Kenya]]\n[[Category:Forum for the Restoration of Democracy \u2013 Kenya politicians]]\n[[Category:Kenyan Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Kenyan democracy activists]]\n[[Category:Kenyan Luo people]]\n[[Category:Kenyan Luo politicians]]\n[[Category:Leipzig University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Kenya)]]\n[[Category:National Development Party (Kenya) politicians]]\n[[Category:Orange Democratic Movement politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Kisumu County]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Kenya]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Kenya]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Kenyan politician}}\n{{Multiple issues\n|{{BLP sources|date=August 2017}}\n{{lead too long|date=August 2017}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name             = Raila Odinga\n| term_start = 9 April 2013 - 18 Jan 2018\n| predecessor = [[Uhuru Kenyatta]]\n| president = [[Uhuru Kenyatta]]\n| office1          = [[African Union High Representative for Infrastructure Development]]\n| 1blankname1      = [[Chairperson of the African Union Commission|Chair]]\n| 1namedata1       = [[Moussa Faki]]\n| term_start1      = 20 October 2018\n| term_end1        = \n| predecessor1     = [[Elisabeth Tankeu]] {{small|(2011){{Ref label|aab|b}}}}\n| office3          = [[Ministry of infrastructure|Minister of Roads, <br />Public Works and Housing]]\n| predecessor3     = William Cheruiyot Morogo\n| president3       = [[Mwai Kibaki]]\n| party            = [[Forum for the Restoration of Democracy]] {{small|(Before 1992)}}<br />[[Forum for the Restoration of Democracy \u2013 Kenya|Forum for the Restoration of Democracy-Kenya]] {{small|(1992\u20131994)}}<br />[[National Development Party (Kenya)|National Development Party]] {{small|(1994\u20132002)}}<br />[[Kenya African National Union]] {{small|(2000\u20132002)}}<br />[[Liberal Democratic Party (Kenya)|Liberal Democratic Party]] {{small|(2002\u20132005)}}<br />[[Orange Democratic Movement]] {{small|(2005\u2013present)}}\n| deputy2          = [[Musalia Mudavadi]]<br />[[Uhuru Kenyatta]]\n| office2          = 2nd [[Prime Minister of Kenya]]\n| predecessor2     = [[Jomo Kenyatta]] {{small|(1964){{Ref label|aaa|a}}}}\n| president2       = [[Mwai Kibaki]]\n| successor2       = ''Office abolished''\n| successor3       = [[Soita Shitanda]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=y|1945|1|7}}\n| birth_place      = [[Maseno]], [[Kenya Colony|Kenya]]\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| otherparty       = [[Coalition for Reforms and Democracy]] {{small|(2012\u20132017)}}<br />[[National Super Alliance]] {{small|(2017\u2013present)}}\n| spouse           = {{marriage|[[Ida Odinga]]|1973}}\n| children         = 4\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Nairobi]]<br />[[Leipzig University]]<br />[[Otto von Guericke University Magdeburg|Magdeburg University]]\n| website          = {{url|rao.co.ke|Official website}}<br />{{url|twitter.com/RailaOdinga|Official Twitter}}\n| term_start2      = 17 April 2008\n| term_end2        = 9 April 2013\n| term_start3      = 14 January 2003\n| term_end3        = 21 November 2005\n| office4          = [[Energy minister|Minister for Energy]]\n| president4       = [[Daniel arap Moi]]\n| term_start4      = 11 June 2001\n| term_end4        = 30 December 2002\n| predecessor4     = [[Francis Masakhalia]]\n| successor4       = [[Simeon Nyachae]]\n| office5          = [[Member of Parliament (Kenya)|Member of Parliament]]<br/>for [[Langata Constituency|Langata]] \n| term_start5      = 29 December 1992\n| term_end5        = 17 January 2013\n| predecessor5     = [[Philip Leakey]]\n| successor5       = Joash Olum\n| office6          = [[National Super Alliance]]<br /> People's President\n| term_start6      = 30 January 2018\n\n| term_end6        = \n| president6      = [[Uhuru Kenyatta]] \n| predecessor6     = Office created\n| successor6       = \n| relatives        = \n| image            = Raila A. Odinga.jpg\n| caption          = Odinga in 2017\n| footnotes        = <small> a. {{note|aaa}}[[Prime Minister of Kenya|Office of the Prime Minister]] vacant from 12 December 1964 to 17 April 2008.<br />b. {{note|aab}}Office vacant from 16 October 2011 to 20 October 2018; [[Elisabeth Tankeu]] served as the [[African Union]] Commissioner of Trade and Industry.</small>\n}}\n\n'''Raila Amolo Odinga ''' is a Kenyan politician who served as the [[Leader of the Opposition]] from 2013 - 14 Jan 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raila-odinga.com/biography |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218214305/http://www.raila-odinga.com/biography |archivedate=18 February 2013 |title=Biography: Raila Odinga |website=raila-odinga.com |accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Okwembah |first=David |date=1 March 2013 |title=Raila Odinga: Third time lucky in Kenya? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21587054 |newspaper=BBC News |accessdate=6 September 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228091914/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21587054 |archivedate=28 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was the Member of Parliament (MP) for [[Langata Constituency|Langata]] from 1992 to 2013. He served in the [[Cabinet of Kenya]] as Minister of Energy from 2001 to 2002, and as the Minister of Roads, Public Works and Housing from 2003 to 2005. Odinga was appointed [[African Union High Representative for Infrastructure Development|High Representative for Infrastructure Development]] at the [[African Union Commission]] in 2018.\n\nHe was the main opposition candidate in the [[2007 Kenyan presidential election|2007 presidential election]], running against incumbent [[Mwai Kibaki]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2000173013/how-mwai-kibaki-raila-odinga-power-sharing-deal-was-struck|title=How Mwai Kibaki, Raila Odinga power sharing deal was struck|first=Faith|last=Ronoh|website=standardmedia.co.ke|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020191701/https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2000173013/how-mwai-kibaki-raila-odinga-power-sharing-deal-was-struck|archivedate=20 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the subsequent [[2013 Kenyan presidential election|presidential election 5 years later]] he placed second against [[Uhuru Kenyatta]], garnering 5,340,546 votes, which represented 43.28% of the total votes cast.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/09/us-kenyan-elections-announcement-idUSBRE92717V20130309 Kenyatta was declared winner of Kenya's presidential vote] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513154224/http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/09/us-kenyan-elections-announcement-idUSBRE92717V20130309 |date=13 May 2013 }}. Reuters. Retrieved on 10 April 2013.</ref> He made another run for the presidency in August 2017 against Uhuru Kenyatta and lost<ref>[https://public.rts.iebc.or.ke/results/results.html IEBC Public Real-time Results Transmission Portal shows that Uhuru Kenyatta won] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808150433/https://public.rts.iebc.or.ke/results/results.html |date=8 August 2017 }} IEBC. Retrieved 17 September 2017.</ref> after the chairman of the electoral body declared Uhuru Kenyatta as the winner with 54% of the votes cast to Odinga's 43%.<ref>[http://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/Kenya-elections-results-president-uhuru-raila/1064-4053260-rko2c6/index.html Odinga's fourth loss in his attempts to be president of Kenya] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918021357/http://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/Kenya-elections-results-president-uhuru-raila/1064-4053260-rko2c6/index.html |date=18 September 2017 }}. Nation Media Group. Retrieved on 17 September 2017.</ref> This outcome was eventually annulled by the Supreme Court following findings that the election was marred by \"illegalities and irregularities\".\nA subsequent fresh election ordered by the Court was won by Uhuru Kenyatta when Odinga declined to participate citing inadequate reforms to enable a fair process in the repeat poll.\n\nSon of the first [[Vice President of Kenya]], [[Jaramogi Oginga Odinga]], he draws a large chunk of his support from various regions in Kenya, most notably the Coastal Region and his native former [[Nyanza Province]]. Odinga is commonly known as \"Baba\", coincidentally: he was an MP at the same time as his father between 1992 and 1994. Other nicknames that have been associated with the premier are such as \"Nyundo\" which is hammer in [[Kiswahili]], \"Tinga\" which means tractor in Kiswahili a symbol of his National Development Party, NDP, \"Agwambo\" meaning a man who is unpredictable and 'BABA' which means the political father.\n\nOdinga first ran as a presidential contender in the 1997 elections, coming third after President [[Daniel arap Moi]] of KANU and [[Mwai Kibaki]] of the [[Democratic Party (Kenya)|Democratic Party]]. He contested for President again in the December 2007 elections on an [[Orange Democratic Movement]] (ODM) ticket.\n\nIn readiness for that poll, on 1 September 2007, Odinga was picked as ODM's presidential nominee to face off with PNU's Kibaki in the current General Election. He managed to garner significant support in the 2007 general election. According to the electoral body at the time (the ECK), he swept the majority of the votes in [[Rift Valley Province|Rift Valley]] (Kenya's most populous area), [[Western Province (Kenya)|Western]], his native [[Nyanza Province|Nyanza]], and [[Coast Province|Coast]]. Kibaki on the other hand won majority votes in [[Nairobi County|Nairobi]] (the capital), [[North Eastern Province (Kenya)|North Eastern province]], [[Central Province (Kenya)|Central province]] and [[Eastern Province (Kenya)|Eastern province]], taking 4 provinces against Odinga's 4. Odinga's ODM party got 99 out of the 210 seats in the parliament, making it the single largest party in parliament.\n\nThe Kriegler report, commissioned to investigate the violent aftermath of the 2007 elections and alleged vote-rigging, stated that about 1.2 million dead voters existed in the voters register, raising serious doubts to the integrity of the election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/business/article/2000008868/in-kisumu-dead-voters-showed-up-at-the-polls |title=In Kisumu, dead voters 'showed up' at the polls |publisher=The Standard |date=2010-05-02 |accessdate=2017-09-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903080047/https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/business/article/2000008868/in-kisumu-dead-voters-showed-up-at-the-polls |archivedate=3 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 30 December 2007, the chairman of the Kenyan [[Electoral Commission of Kenya|election commission]] declared Odinga's opponent, incumbent president Kibaki, the winner of the presidential election by a slim margin of about 230,000 votes. Odinga disputed the results, alleging [[electoral fraud|fraud]] by the election commission. However he refused to follow due process of petitioning the courts, believing that the courts were under manipulation by Kibaki and so could not give a fair and impartial hearing.\n\nMost opinion polls had speculated that Odinga would defeat the president, though the margin kept narrowing as election day neared. Independent international observers have since stated that the poll was marred by irregularities in favor of both PNU and ODM, especially at the final vote tallying stages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationmedia.com/dailynation/nmgcontententry.asp?category_id=1&newsid=114851 |title=\"Observers criticize poll standards\" |accessdate=2008-01-20 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080121063149/http://www.nationmedia.com/dailynation/nmgcontententry.asp?category_id=1&newsid=114851 |archivedate=21 January 2008 |df=dmy-all }}, [[Daily Nation]], 18 January 2008.</ref> Many ODM supporters across the country [[civil unrest in Kenya (2007\u20132008)|rioted]] against the announced election results, triggering the worst national violence in post-independent Kenya.\n \nBesides his father, Odinga is identified as one of the leading forces behind the democratization process of Kenya, particularly during the repressive regime of President [[Daniel arap Moi]] (1978-2002) and the lead-up to the adoption of the new Constitution (2010) that re-affirmed many formerly neglected fundamental rights.\n\nIn 2017, Odinga [[2017 Kenyan general election|vied yet again for the presidency]], but lost to Uhuru Kenyatta. Odinga contested the election result in the Supreme Court, which nullified the results and called new elections as a result of electoral irregularities. Despite the Supreme Court ruling, Odinga announced on 10 October 2017 that he would withdraw from the second Presidential election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-41572128|title=Raila Odinga quits Kenya election re-run|date=10 October 2017|via=www.bbc.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021095749/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-41572128|archivedate=21 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRaila Odinga was born at the Anglican Church Missionary Society Hospital, in [[Maseno]], [[Kisumu District]], [[Nyanza Province]] on 7 January 1945 to [[Mary Ajuma Odinga]] and [[Jaramogi Oginga Odinga]]. His father served as the first [[Vice President of Kenya]] under President [[Jomo Kenyatta]].<ref name=usatoday>{{cite news|first=Heidi|last=Vogt|title=Kibaki, Odinga have a long history |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2008-02-28-4157951089_x.htm |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[USA Today]] |date=28 February 2008 |accessdate=9 August 2012}}</ref> He went to Kisumu Union Primary School, Maranda Primary and [[Maranda School]] where he dropped out in 1962. He spent the next two years at the [[Herder Institut]], a part of the [[Philology|philological faculty]] at the [[University of Leipzig]] in [[East Germany]].<ref name=\"bridge\">Daily Nation, 9 December 2007: [http://politics.nationmedia.com/inner.asp?fs=1&sid=520 aila Odinga: I\u2019m the bridge] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081002173329/http://politics.nationmedia.com/inner.asp?fs=1&sid=520 |date=2 October 2008 }}</ref> He received a scholarship that in 1965 sent him to the [[Magdeburg|Technical School, Magdeburg]] (now a part of [[Otto-von-Guericke University Magdeburg]]) in [[East Germany|the GDR]]. In 1970, he graduated with a diploma. While studying in [[East Berlin]] during the [[Cold War]], as a Kenyan he was able to visit [[West Berlin]] through the [[Checkpoint Charlie]]. When visiting West Berlin, he used to smuggle goods not available in East Berlin and bring them to his friends in East Berlin.<ref name=\"newsweek\">Newsweek Web Exclusive, 22 January 2008: [http://www.newsweek.com/id/97058 The Man Who Would Be President] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029210210/http://www.newsweek.com/id/97058 |date=29 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nHe returned to Kenya in 1970. In 1971 he established the ''Standard Processing Equipment Construction & Erection Ltd'' (later renamed ''East African Spectre''), a company manufacturing liquid petroleum gas cylinders. In 1974, he was appointed group standards manager of the [[Kenya Bureau of Standards]]. In 1978 he was promoted to its Deputy Director, a post he held until his 1982 detention.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}\n\n==Detention==\nIn an era of unrelenting human rights abuse by the Kenya government, Odinga was placed under [[house arrest]] for seven months after evidence seemed to implicate him along with his late father Oginga Odinga for collaborating with the plotters of a [[1982 Kenyan coup|failed coup attempt]] against President [[Daniel arap Moi]] in 1982. Hundreds of Kenyan civilians and thousands of rebel soldiers died in the coup. Several foreigners also lost their lives. Odinga was later charged with treason and detained without trial for six years.<ref>[[Human Rights Watch|Human rights Watch]], 1992: [https://www.hrw.org/reports/1992/WR92/AFW-03.htm Kenya: Human Rights Developments] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128133605/https://www.hrw.org/reports/1992/WR92/AFW-03.htm |date=28 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\nA biography released 14 years later in July 2006 apparently with Odinga's approval, indicated that Odinga was far more involved in the attempted coup than he had previously admitted. After its publication, some Members of Parliament in Kenya called for Odinga to be arrested and charged,<ref>The Standard, 17 July 2006: [http://allafrica.com/stories/200607171148.html \u201982 coup: Arrest Raila, say MPs] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016000149/http://allafrica.com/stories/200607171148.html |date=16 October 2012 }}</ref> but the [[statute of limitations]] had already passed and, since the information was contained in the biography did not amount to an open confession on his part.<ref>[[The Standard (Kenya)|The Standard]], 21 July 2006: [http://allafrica.com/stories/200607210225.html Why A-G won\u2019t charge Raila] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016000157/http://allafrica.com/stories/200607210225.html |date=16 October 2012 }}</ref> Among some of his most painful experiences was when his mother died in 1984 but the prison wardens took two months to inform him of her death.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}\n\nHe was released on 6 February 1988 only to be rearrested in September 1988 for his pro-democracy and human rights agitation at a time when the country continued to descend deep into the throes of poor governance.<ref>[[University of Pennsylvania]], African Studies Centre, East Africa Living Encyclopedia: [http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Hornet/irin_121397.html Kenya: IRIN Election Briefing, 12/13/97] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070316203333/http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Hornet/irin_121397.html |date=16 March 2007 }}</ref> and the despotism of single-party rule. [[multi-party system|multi-party democracy]] Kenya, was then, by law, a [[one-party state]]. His encounters with the authoritarian government generated an aura of intrigue about him and it was probably due to this his political followers, christened him \"Agwambo\", [[Luo language|Luo]] for \"The Mystery\" or \"Unpredictable\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2000230378/meet-woman-who-gave-raila-odinga-the-name-agwambo|title=Meet woman who gave Raila Odinga the name \u2018Agwambo\u2019|first=Kevine|last=Omollo|website=standardmedia.co.ke|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905055306/https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2000230378/meet-woman-who-gave-raila-odinga-the-name-agwambo|archivedate=5 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> or \"Jakom\", meaning Chairman.\n\nOdinga was released on 12 June 1989, only to be incarcerated again on 5 July 1990, together with [[Kenneth Matiba]], and former Nairobi Mayor [[Charles Rubia]], multiparty system and human rights crusaders .<ref>University of Pennsylvania, African Studies Centre, East Africa Living Encyclopedia: [http://www.africa.upenn.edu/NEH/khistory.htm Kenya \u2013 History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127162720/http://www.africa.upenn.edu/NEH/khistory.htm |date=27 November 2014 }}</ref> Odinga was finally released on 21 June 1991, and in October, he fled the country to Norway amid indications that the increasingly corrupt Kenyan government was attempting to assassinate him without success .<ref>The Standard, 16 July 2006: {{cite web |url=http://www.eastandard.net/archives/sunday/hm_news/news.php?articleid=1143955395&date=19%2F07%2F2006 |title=Day Raila fled disguised as priest |accessdate=2017-07-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080112082224/http://www.eastandard.net/archives/sunday/hm_news/news.php?articleid=1143955395&date=19%2F07%2F2006 |archivedate=12 January 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Multi-party politics==\nAt the time of Odinga's departure to Norway, the [[Forum for the Restoration of Democracy]] (FORD), a movement formed to agitate for the return of multi-party democracy to Kenya, was newly formed. In February 1992, Odinga returned to join FORD, then led by his father [[Jaramogi Oginga Odinga]]. He was elected Vice Chairman of the General Purposes Committee of the party. In the months running up to the 1992 General Election, FORD split into [[Ford-Kenya political party|Ford Kenya]], led by Odinga's father [[Jaramogi Oginga Odinga]], and [[Forum for the Restoration of Democracy-Asili|FORD-Asili]] led by [[Kenneth Matiba]]. Odinga became Ford-Kenya's Deputy Director of Elections. Odinga won the [[Langata Constituency]] parliamentary seat, previously held by [[Philip Leakey]] of KANU. Odinga became the second father of multi- party democracy in Kenya after Kenneth Matiba.<ref name=\"multiparty\">Center for Multiparty Democracy: [http://www.cmd.or.ke/images/Politics%20and%20Paliamenterians%20in%20Kenya.pdf Politics and Parliamentarians in Kenya 1944\u20132007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081028212845/http://www.cmd.or.ke/images/Politics%20and%20Paliamenterians%20in%20Kenya.pdf |date=28 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Jaramogi Oginga Odinga]] died in January 1994, and [[Michael Wamalwa Kijana]] succeeded him as FORD-Kenya chairman, Odinga challenged him for the party leadership. The elections were marred by controversy after which Odinga resigned from FORD-Kenya to join the [[National Development Party (Kenya)|National Development Party]] (NDP).\n\nIn his first bid for the presidency in the 1997 General Election, Odinga finished third after President Moi, the incumbent, and Democratic Party candidate [[Mwai Kibaki]]. He however retained his position as the Langata MP.<ref name=\"multiparty\"/>\n\nIn a surprise move, Odinga decided to support Moi, his arch-enemy, even entering into a political merger between his party, NDP, and Moi's much-hated [[Kenya African National Union|KANU]] party, which many Kenyans likened to the yoke of oppression. The merger was called New KANU. Previous admirers of Odinga now saw him as a sell-out to a cause he had once championed by closing ranks with a despot. He accepted a position in Moi's cabinet as Energy Minister, serving from June 2001 to 2002, during Moi's final term.\n\nIn the subsequent KANU elections held later that year, he was elected the party's Secretary General (replacing [[Joseph Kamotho]]).<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/200208060047.html Kenya: Saitoti, Raila And Kamotho Hold Breakfast Meeting] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020917071057/http://allafrica.com/stories/200208060047.html |date=17 September 2002 }}. allafrica.com. 6 August 2002</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Joe Khamisi|title=The Politics of Betrayal: Diary of a Kenyan Legislator|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=saw3XU7VaI4C+|date= 2011|publisher=Trafford Publishing|isbn=978-1-4269-8676-5|page=15}}</ref> It was apparent to many that Odinga hoped to ascend to the presidency through KANU and with Moi's support.\n\nIn 2002, much to the chagrin of Odinga and many other hopefuls in the party, Moi endorsed [[Uhuru Kenyatta]] \u2013 son of Kenya's first president [[Jomo Kenyatta]] but a relative newcomer in politics \u2013 to be his successor. Moi publicly asked Odinga and others to support Uhuru as well.<ref>BBC News, 16 September 2002: [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/2261085.stm Anti-Moi alliance emerging] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040717172624/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/2261085.stm |date=17 July 2004 }}</ref> This was taken as an affront by many of the party loyalists who felt they were being asked to make way for a newcomer who, unlike them, had done little to build the party. Odinga and other KANU members, including [[Kalonzo Musyoka]], [[George Saitoti]] and [[Joseph Kamotho]], opposed this step arguing that the then 38-year-old Uhuru was politically inexperienced and lacked the leadership qualities needed to govern. Moi stood his ground, maintaining that the country's leadership needed to pass to the younger generation.\n\nDissent ran through the party with some members openly disagreeing with Moi, despite his reputation as an autocrat. It was then that the Rainbow Movement was founded, comprising disgruntled KANU members who exited KANU. The exodus, led by Odinga, saw most big names fleeing the party. Moi was left with his handpicked successor almost alone with a party reduced to an empty shell with poor electoral prospects. The Rainbow Movement went on to join the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Kenya)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (LDP), which later teamed up with opposition Mwai Kibaki's [[National Alliance Party of Kenya]] (NAK), a coalition of several other parties, to form the [[National Rainbow Coalition]] ([[National Rainbow Coalition|NARC]]).\n\nAmid fears that this opposition \"super alliance\", would fail to unite and rally behind a common candidate as in previous occasions thus easily hand victory to the government, Odinga declared \"''Kibaki tosha''\", Swahili for \"Kibaki is sufficient\", an endorsement of a Kibaki ticket. This resolved the matter of candidacy and Narc went on to defeat Moi's protege, Uhuru Kenyatta. The opposition won a landslide 67% of the vote, dealing a humiliating blow to Moi. Odinga led the campaign for Kibaki throughout the country while Kibaki was bedridden and incapacitated following an accident in which he sustained injuries.\n\n==Dissent from within==\n[[File:Gordon Brown Raila Odinga.JPG|thumb|Odinga with [[Gordon Brown]] at [[Kibera]]]]\nOn assuming office, President Kibaki did not appoint Odinga as Prime Minister in the new government, contrary to a pre-election MOU. (Kenya's constitution had no provision for Prime minister yet); neither did he give LDP (Odinga's faction) half of the cabinet positions as per the MOU. He instead sought to entrench and increase his own NAK's side in cabinet, even appointing MPs from the opposition parties (KANU and FORD people) to the cabinet.<ref>BBC News, 30 September 2003: [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3356431.stm Uproar over Kenya leader's decree] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040720215552/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3356431.stm |date=20 July 2004 }}</ref>\n\nThe perceived \"betrayal\" started a simmering disquiet which in time led to an open rebellion and a split within the cabinet. A key point of disagreement was a proposed new constitution for the country, which was a major campaign issue that had united Kibaki's NAK and Odinga's LDP in the campaign. This constitution included provisions to trim presidential powers to rein in what was seen as an autocratic presidency, a feature of both the Moi and first president Jomo Kenyatta's regimes which had led to a lot of power abuse and an unaccountable leadership.\n\nOnce in power however, Kibaki's government instituted a Constitutional Committee which turned around and submitted a draft constitution that was perceived to consolidate presidential powers and weaken regional governments, contrary to the pre-election draft.\n\nOdinga opposed this and went on to campaign with his LDP cabinet colleagues on the referendum 'No' side, opposing the President and his lieutenants in a bruising countrywide campaign. When the document was put to a [[2005 Kenyan constitutional referendum|referendum]] on 21 November 2005, the government lost by a 57% to 43% margin. Embarrassingly for Kibaki, out of 8 provinces, only one ( Central Province where his tribe the Kikuyu are dominant) voted \"yes\" for the document, isolating his own tribe from the rest of Kenya and exposing his campaign as ethnic- based.\n\nA shell-shocked and disappointed President Kibaki sacked the entire cabinet on 23 November 2005. When it was reconstituted two weeks later, Odinga and the entire LDP group were left out.\n\nThis led to the formation of a new opposition outfit, the Orange Democratic Movement (ODM) \u2013 an Orange was the symbol for the \"No\" vote in the constitutional referendum.\n\nIn January 2006, Odinga was reported to have told police that he believed his life was in danger, having received assassination threats.<ref>BBC News, 10 January 2006: [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/4599834.stm Kenyan opponent 'fears for life'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060113105542/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/4599834.stm |date=13 January 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==2007 presidential election==\nOn 12 July 2007, with Kibaki's reelection bid drawing close, Odinga alleged that the government was withholding [[Identity document|identity cards]] from voters in opposition strongholds with intention to skew the election in favour of Kibaki. He also claimed that the intended creation of 30 new constituencies was a means by the government to fraudulently engineer victory in the [[2007 Kenyan parliamentary election|December 2007 parliamentary election]].<ref>David Schlesinger and Barry Moody, [http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=87&art_id=nw20070713104933431C315734 \"Presidential hopeful doubts free, fair polls\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060615021453/http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1 |date=15 June 2006 }}, Reuters (''IOL''), 13 July 2007.</ref>\n\n[[File:Raila and the media.jpg|thumb|Odinga addressing the Kenyan media during the [[2007\u201308 Kenyan crisis]]]]\nIn August 2007, the Odinga's own Orange Democratic Movement-Kenya suffered a setback when it split into two, with Odinga becoming head of the Orange Democratic Movement (ODM) while the other faction, the ODM-K, was headed by [[Kalonzo Musyoka]] who parted ways with Odinga.<ref>Peter Clottey, [http://www.voanews.com/english/Africa/2007-08-16-voa1.cfm \"Kenya's Opposition Split Brightens Kibaki's Second Term Bid\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070817225414/http://www.voanews.com/english/Africa/2007-08-16-voa1.cfm |date=17 August 2007 }}, [[Voice of America|VOA News]], 16 August 2007.</ref>\n\nOn 1 September 2007, the ODM elected Odinga as its presidential candidate in a National Delegates Conference held at the [[Moi International Sports Centre]] in Nairobi. Odinga received 2,656 votes; the only other candidates who received significant numbers of votes were [[Musalia Mudavadi]] with 391 and [[William Ruto]] with 368. Earlier, [[Najib Balala]] had withdrawn his candidature and endorsed Odinga.<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/200709010028.html \"Kenya: It's Raila for President\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926231155/http://allafrica.com/stories/200709010028.html |date=26 September 2007 }}, ''The Standard'', 1 September 2007.</ref> The defeated candidates expressed their support for Odinga afterward, and Mudavadi was named as his [[running mate]].<ref>Maina Muiruri, [http://www.eastandard.net/InsidePage.php?id=1143973907 \"ODM \u2018pentagon\u2019 promises to keep the team intact\"]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''The Standard'' (Kenya), 2 September 2007.</ref>\n\nOdinga then launched his [[Political campaign|presidential campaign]] in [[Uhuru Park]] in Nairobi on 6 October 2007.\n\nOdinga's bid for the presidency however failed when after the 27 December [[2007 Kenyan presidential election|presidential election]], the Electoral Commission declared Kibaki the winner on 30 December 2007, placing him ahead of Odinga by about 232,000 votes. [[Jeffrey Sachs]] (Professor of Economics and Director of [[the Earth Institute]] at [[Columbia University]], and Special Advisor to former [[United Nations Secretary-General|UN Secretary General]]) faulted the United States' approach to the post-election crisis and recommended an independent recount of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/?page=2008%5C01%5C25%5Cstory_25-1-2008_pg3_4 |title=Leading News Resource of Pakistan |publisher=Daily Times |date=25 January 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606183629/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/?page=2008%5C01%5C25%5Cstory_25-1-2008_pg3_4 |archivedate=6 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Raila Amolo Odinga with Obamas.jpg|left|thumb|President [[Barack Obama]] and First Lady [[Michelle Obama]] of the United States pose for a photo during a reception at the Metropolitan Museum in New York with Raila Odinga, [[Prime Minister of Kenya|Prime Minister of the Republic of Kenya]], and his wife, Mrs. [[Ida Odinga]]]]\nOdinga and his ODM leaders rallied against the decision with James Orengo and Prof. Nyong'o calling for mass action. Later violence broke out in the country.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/12/31/2129125.htm?section=world \"Kibaki re-elected Kenyan president: official results\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090823052314/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/12/31/2129125.htm?section=world |date=23 August 2009 }}, AFP (abc.net.au), 31 December 2007.</ref>\nThe government's response was heavy-handed as it deployed police and paramilitary units to counter public protests.\n\nFollowing two months of unrest, which led to the death of about 1000 people and displacement of about 250, 000, a deal between Odinga and Kibaki, which provided for power-sharing and the creation of the post of Prime Minister, was signed in February 2008; it was brokered by former UN Secretary General [[Kofi Annan]]. Odinga was sworn in as Prime Minister, along with the power-sharing Cabinet, on 17 April 2008. The post of Prime Minister was last held by [[Jomo Kenyatta]] between 1963 and 1964 following independence. Odinga is thus the second person in Kenya's history to hold the position.<ref>Eric Ombok, [https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=abAJ_3lpr8WA&refer=home \"Kenya's Raila Odinga Sworn in as Prime Minister, Ending Crisis\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613163056/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |date=13 June 2010 }}, Bloomberg.com, 17 April 2008.</ref>\n\n[[File:Prime Minister of Kenya (7752141076).jpg|left|thumb|[[British Foreign Secretary]] [[William Hague]] meeting Odinga, then Prime Minister of Kenya, in London, 10 August 2012]]\n\n==2013 presidential election==\n[[File:Raila Odinga speaking at visit to Peace Corps.jpg|thumb|Odinga speaking at a visit to Peace Corps]]\n\nThe next presidential election in which Odinga was to run was the 2013 March poll, involving Kibaki's handover of power. Uncertainty loomed over Odinga's main rivals, Uhuru Kenyatta and William Ruto, who had both been indicted by the [[International Criminal Court|ICC]] of the Hague for their alleged role in the 2007 election violence. \nDespite their pending case, the duo had been nominated by the Jubilee party with Uhuru as presidential candidate and Ruto as running mate. \nMany felt they were unfit to run for office before clearing their names from such serious crimes while others felt that their opponents were trying to unfairly exploit the situation by eliminating them from the race and pave the way for their easy victory.\n\nA Synovate survey released in October 2012 found Odinga to enjoy a leading 45 percent approval rate against Uhuru and Ruto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201104170037.html |title=allAfrica.com: Kenya: Raila's Ratings Fall But Still Ahead of the Pack |publisher=allAfrica |date=15 April 2010 |accessdate=15 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nOdinga's party, Orange Democratic Movement (ODM) joined Kalonzo Musyoka's Wiper Party and Moses Wetangula's Ford Kenya (FK) in a CORD coalition (Coalition for Reforms and Democracy) for the presidential race with Odinga as the presidential candidate and Kalonzo as his running mate to face Jubilee's coalition ( [[Uhuru Kenyatta]]'s (The National Alliance \u2013 TNA), [[William Ruto]]'s (United Republican Party \u2013 URP), [[Charity Ngilu]]'s (National Rainbow Coalition \u2013 NARC) and [[Najib Balala]]'s (Republican Congress \u2013 RC)).\n\nA number of western countries were not in favour of the Uhuru and Ruto candidacy in view of their pending ICC cases and association with crimes against humanity. Former UN Secretary General Koffi Annan voiced his reservations, as did former US Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs [[Johnnie Carson]] who cautioned against the election of Uhuru Kenyatta and William Ruto. He was notably quoted as saying that \"Choices have consequences, \" referring to the fate of US-Kenyan relations, with a Uhuru administration.\n\n[[File:Opening Plenary - World Economic Forum on Africa 2008.jpg|left|thumb|Odinga, Prime Minister of Kenya, with, from left, [[Pierre Nkurunziza]], [[President of Burundi]], [[Bingu Wa Mutharika]], [[President of Malawi]], [[Thabo Mbeki]], [[President of South Africa]], [[Klaus Schwab]], Founder and Executive Chairman, [[World Economic Forum]], and [[John Agyekum Kufuor]], [[President of Ghana]], during the Opening Plenary of the World Economic Forum on Africa 2008 in [[Cape Town]], South Africa, 4 June 2008]]\n\nOdinga ran for President in the elections held on 4 March 2013 and garnered 5,340,546 votes (43.70%) out of the 12,221,053 valid votes cast. The winner, Uhuru Kenyatta garnered 6,173,433 votes (50.51%). As this was above the 50% plus 1 vote threshold, Uhuru won it on the first round without requiring a run-off between the top two candidates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iebc.or.ke/index.php/resources/downloads/item/summary-of-2013-presidential-results-declared-on-932013?category_id=26 |title=SUMMARY OF 2013 PRESIDENTIAL RESULTS DECLARED ON 9/3/2013 |publisher=IEBC |date=3 April 2013 |accessdate=3 April 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315145243/http://www.iebc.or.ke/index.php/resources/downloads/item/summary-of-2013-presidential-results-declared-on-932013?category_id=26 |archivedate=15 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission (IEBC) therefore officially declared Uhuru Kenyatta the president elect on Saturday 9 March at 2:44pm. Uhuru was set to take office as Kenya's 4th president.\n\nHowever, in a press conference shortly after the results were announced, Odinga said that the election had been marred by massive failures of the Biometric Voter Registration(BVR) kits, EVID (electronic voter identification or \"Pollbooks\"), RTS (results transmission system or \"tallying system\") and the RPS (results presentation or \"transmissions system\"). He claimed that the manual tallying was suspect leaving him no choice but to [[The Kenya Presidential Election Petition 2013]] contest the result in Kenya's highest court, The Supreme Court.\n\nIn anticipation of the legal challenge, Odinga and his lawyers George Oraro, Mutula Kilonzo, and James Orengo, secretly instructed Raj Pal Senna,<ref>[http://rajpalsenna.com/index/ Landing Page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102062042/http://rajpalsenna.com/index/ |date=2 November 2014 }}. Raj Pal Senna (25 April 2014). Retrieved on 21 April 2015.</ref> a Management Consultant from Barcelona to carry out a forensic investigation of the technology used in the Kenyan General Election 2013, during which the IEBC made claims on TV and media that there were \"technological challenges\", that servers overloaded and that database crashed.<ref>[http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/print/2000083919/the-raila-supreme-court-evidence Standard Digital News \u2013 Kenya : Breaking News, Latest, Business, Jobs, Football, Travel, Tourism, Elections, National, Nairobi, County, East Africa, Media] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102041411/http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/print/2000083919/the-raila-supreme-court-evidence |date=2 November 2014 }}. Standardmedia.co.ke (15 April 2015). Retrieved on 21 April 2015.</ref><ref>[https://www.ktnkenya.tv/?articleID=2000083919&story_title=what-raila-failed-to-tell-in-petition-against-uhuru&pageNo=2 Standard Digital News \u2013 Kenya : What Raila failed to tell in petition against Uhuru] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102035800/https://www.ktnkenya.tv/?articleID=2000083919&story_title=what-raila-failed-to-tell-in-petition-against-uhuru&pageNo=2 |date=2 November 2014 }}. Ktnkenya.tv. Retrieved on 21 April 2015.</ref>\n\nKenya's chief justice Dr. [[Willy Mutunga]] announced on Monday, 11 March that the Supreme Court was fully formed and ready to deliver its judgements within 14 days as stipulated by the constitution of Kenya.\n\nDuring the Petition hearing, Chief Justice Willy Mutunga made a finding rejecting second affidavit of Odinga which comprised 900 pages, on the basis that it amounted to \"new evidence\" which is not permitted under the Constitution. Subsequently, The Supreme Court issued a ruling dismissing the petition on 30 March 2013. The Supreme Court while declaring Uhuru the next President also declared that the [[Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission|IEBC]] should not have included the invalid/spoilt votes in the calculation of the final figures and percentages.\nChief Justice Willy Mutunga also directed that the EACC (Ethics and Anti Corruption Commission) and the DPP (Director of Public Prosecutions) carry out a criminal investigation of the IEBC in relation to the BVR, EVID, RTS and RPS.<ref name=\"businessdailyafrica.com\">[http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Kenya-poll-officials-IT-vendors-face-probe-over-glitches-/-/539546/1750444/-/bax88r/-/index.html IEBC officials may be prosecuted over gadget failure \u2013 Politics and policy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102070134/http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Kenya-poll-officials-IT-vendors-face-probe-over-glitches-/-/539546/1750444/-/bax88r/-/index.html |date=2 November 2014 }}. businessdailyafrica.com (16 April 2013). Retrieved on 21 April 2015.</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Supreme Court of Kenya|supreme court]] [[The Kenya Presidential Election Petition 2013|dismissed his petition]] Odinga flew to South Africa to avoid attending the Inauguration of Uhuru Kenyatta, held on 9 April 2013 at Moi Sports Complex at Kasarani, Nairobi. The swearing ceremony marked the end of his premiership.\n\nIn an important development, the full investigation findings were published as the [[OpCo Report]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150711110418/http://kenya-legal.com/main/efiles/1/15/op-co-report-election-4-mar-2013 OpCo Report: Election 4 Mar 2013]. kenya-legal.com (24 January 2014)</ref> on the website www.kenya-legal.com and inspired the documentary \"50+1 \u2013 The Inside Story\"<ref>[http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/ktn/video/watch/2000077350/-part-one-the-inside-story-50-1-what-really-happened-during-the-2013-elections Standard Digital News \u2013 KTN : KTN Video | Part One: The Inside Story 50+1 (What really happened during the 2013 elections)]. Standardmedia.co.ke. (25 April 2014).</ref> by KTN journalists John Namu and Mohammed Ali.\n\nThis documentary examines the history of election fraud and the history of corruption in the Judiciary, and in which Odinga claims that it can not be ruled out that it was a deliberate act or omission by the Court not to subject the technical evidence to scrutiny because the outcome would invalidate the entire election process and discredit the IEBC.\n\n==2017 presidential elections==\n===Claims of election rigging===\nOdinga, through his lawyer James Orengo, Otiende Amollo and Clifford Ochieng claimed that forces associated with his main competitor Uhuru Kenyatta had hacked into the IEBC (Kenya's electoral body) server and tampered with its database. He stated that the results that were being transmitted by IEBC were false because they had been manipulated via a computer algorithm designed to maintain an 11% gap between him and Uhuru's votes. As such, he proved the votes were not real votes cast by human voters but the outcome of a computer generated formula producing artificial values. This intrusion into IEBC's system, he further said, affected not just the presidential results but the entire election, including the votes cast for MPs, Senators, Governors and Women Representatives. He called the alleged intrusion \"the biggest vote theft in Kenya\u2019s history.\" Later while vote tallying was still in progress and the country was awaiting announcement of the final results, Odinga revealed that his team had received information from a confidential source in IEBC indicating that results from its server showed him leading with an unassailable 8 million votes over Uhuru's 7 million votes. Based on this, he demanded he be declared the 5th [[President of Kenya]].\n\nThe IEBC however rejected Odinga's contention, saying the winner could not be announced before the tallying was complete and also being an independent body it could not be compelled by one of the candidates to announce the results.\n\nThe IEBC finally announced the results declaring Uhuru the winner with 8.2 million votes against Odinga's 6.7 million. The results showed massive losses for NASA, with Jubilee invading traditional NASA strongholds. NASA refused to recognize the results.\n\nShortly after Uhuru's declared victory, violence was reported in some parts of the country which are opposition strongholds. However the violence was not of the scale witnessed in the 2007 election aftermath and broke out only sporadically. Both Odinga and President Kenyatta called for public calm.\n\n===Annulment of the presidential election===\nAfter initially declining to take his case to court on the grounds that the court had previously made an unfavourable judgment against him, Odinga reconsidered and lodged a petition.\n\nAfter 2 days of hearing, the judges in a majority 4\u20132 decision returned a verdict on 1 September annulling the presidential results and ordered a new election to be held within 60 days. The court decision, read by Chief Justice David Maraga and widely viewed as unprecedented both in Africa and globally held that the IEBC failed to conduct the election in the manner provided by the Constitution and so could not stand.<ref>{{cite web|last1=FREYTAS-TAMURA|first1=KIMIKO|title=Kenya Supreme Court Nullifies Presidential Election|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/01/world/africa/kenya-election-kenyatta-odinga.html?_r=0|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901210458/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/01/world/africa/kenya-election-kenyatta-odinga.html?_r=0|archivedate=1 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDespite the Supreme Court ruling, Odinga announced his withdrawal from the Presidential election, scheduled for 26 October,<ref name=\"veconomist\">{{cite news|title=Raila Odinga takes a gamble by threatening to boycott Kenya\u2019s election|url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21730121-first-poll-was-annulled-second-may-be-violently-disrupted-raila-odinga|work=[[The Economist]]|date=11 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012061227/https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21730121-first-poll-was-annulled-second-may-be-violently-disrupted-raila-odinga|archivedate=12 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> on 10 October.<ref name=odingwithd>http://ntv.co.ug/news/international/10/oct/2017/i-will-not-be-forced-participate-election-re-run-says-raila-odinga#sthash.Cjs9fhpG.dpbs {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010142116/http://www.ntv.co.ug/news/international/10/oct/2017/i-will-not-be-forced-participate-election-re-run-says-raila-odinga |date=10 October 2017 }}</ref> The reason for his withdrawal was his belief that the election would again not be free or fair, since no electoral process reforms had been made since the annulment of the last election,<ref name=\"veconomist\" /> as well as various defections which occurred from his coalition.<ref name=odingwithd />\n\nIEBC later stated that Odinga had not officially withdrawn from the race for presidency and his would still appear on the ballot on 26 October among other candidates who contested in the 8 August General Elections.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://nairobinews.nation.co.ke/news/iebc-raila-not-withdrawn-presidential-race/|title=IEBC: Raila has not withdrawn from presidential race - Nairobi News|date=2017-10-11|work=Nairobi News|access-date=2017-10-12|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012203220/http://nairobinews.nation.co.ke/news/iebc-raila-not-withdrawn-presidential-race/|archivedate=12 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThis resulted to violent uproar in various parts of the country some few days before and after the repeat polls especially in the NASA dominated zones. Alleged police brutality was reported as independent medic research organization (IMLU) cited 39 deaths and high assault cases\n\n===Swearing in of People's President, and reconciliation===\nOn 30 January, Odinga staged a swearing in ceremony in Nairobi where he named himself 'People's President. Following this ceremony TV stations across Kenya were taken off air. A month and a half later, on 9 March, Odinga and president Uhuru Kenyatta made a joint televised appearance in which they referred to each other as 'brothers,' and agreed to put aside political differences to allow Kenya to move forward.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/30/world/africa/raila-odinga-kenya.html|title=Kenyans Name a \u2018People\u2019s President,\u2019 and TV Broadcasts Are Cut|date=30 January 2018|via=NYTimes.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180202215536/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/30/world/africa/raila-odinga-kenya.html|archivedate=2 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-42905290|title=Kenya TV off air despite court ruling|date=1 February 2018|via=www.bbc.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201111606/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-42905290|archivedate=1 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-43345217 |title=Kenya's Uhuru Kenyatta and Raila Odinga now 'brothers' |date=9 March 2018 |accessdate=20 March 2018 |website=bbc.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312012627/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-43345217 |archivedate=12 March 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== The Building Bridges Initiative ==\nFollowing the March 2018 truce between Mr. Odinga and President Kenyatta, the two commissioned a joint task force that would collect views from Kenyans and report their findings. After touring the country and holding consultative sessions, the team compiled and submitted the report to President Kenyatta at State House Nairobi on 26 November 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001350941/president-uhuru-receives-bbi-report|title=President Uhuru receives BBI report|last=Ogila|first=Japheth|website=The Standard|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> which was followed by a public launch at the Bomas of Kenya the following day.<ref>{{Citation|title=Kenya unites behind BBI at Bomas - VIDEO|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/Delegates-arrive-at-Bomas-of-Kenya-for-BBI-report-launch/1064-5364226-5ec7tg/index.html|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> The efforts by President Kenyatta and Mr. Odinga to bring peace and cohesion in the country were applauded by several leaders locally and internationally with the duo being invited to the [[International Lunch]] in Washington DC, USA in February 2020 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Peace-deal-earns-Uhuru-and-Raila-US-invite/1056-5431876-c5m9da/index.html|title=Peace deal earns Uhuru and Raila US invite|website=Daily Nation|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n===Economics===\nOginga's political ideology can be loosely styled as social democracy, more closely aligned with American left wing politics. His position was once in favour of a parliamentary system as seen when he initially backed a Constitution giving executive powers to a Prime Minister but he subsequently changed to a presidential system with a devolved power structure, which is reflected in Kenya's current constitution.\n\nOdinga is seen as the main force behind devolution now enshrined in Kenya's constitution as an essential part of Kenya's governance system. This was inspired by a feeling that all successive governments under the centralized power structure had consistently abused that power to favour certain areas along political or ethnic lines while denying many regions access to resources and development because of their ethnicity or perceived disloyalty. Devolution aimed to address this and guarantee regions their fair share of resources regardless of their political affiliation or ethnicity.\n\nDue to an economic downturn and extreme drought, Odinga has called for the suspension of taxes on fuels and certain foods that disproportionately impact the poor.\n<ref>Kenya Broadcasting Corporation, 1 June 2011: [http://www.kbc.co.ke/news.asp?nid=70521 Principles Unite in Addressing High Cost of Living] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321070428/http://www.kbc.co.ke/news.asp?nid=70521 |date=21 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOdinga has supported an element of state welfare in the form of cash-transfer programs to low-income people. This is currently implemented but in a limited way to poor, elderly people.\n\n[[File:Foreign Office Minister Henry Bellingham meeting Kenyan Prime Minister Raila Odinga in London, 7 July 2011. (5911639399).jpg|left|thumb|British Foreign Office Minister [[Henry Bellingham (Norfolk MP)|Henry Bellingham]] meeting Odinga in [[London]], 7 July 2011]]\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Raila and Ida Odinga.jpg|thumb|right|Odinga and his wife [[Ida Odinga|Ida]] at a political rally]]\nBaptised as an Anglican Christian in the Church Missionary Society (CMS) in his childhood,<ref>The Standard, 5 November 2007: [http://allafrica.com/stories/200711050379.html ODM promises smooth transition if it wins] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012022613/http://allafrica.com/stories/200711050379.html |date=12 October 2012 }}</ref> Odinga later became a [[Born-Again]] [[Christians|Christian]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/8033376.stm |title='Doomsday' man baptises Kenya PM |publisher=BBC News |date=5 May 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090509213347/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/8033376.stm |archivedate=9 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and is a communicant member of All saints' Cathedral in Nairobi.\n\nOdinga is married to [[Ida Odinga]] (Ida Anyango Oyoo). They live in Karen, Nairobi and have a second home at central Farm, in [[Siaya County]]. The couple have four children: Fidel (1973\u20132015),<ref>{{Cite news\n |last        = Leftie, Peter, Zaddock Angira, Njoki Chege and Stella Cherono\n |title       = Raila family in mourning as eldest son found dead in bed after night partying \u2013 News \u2013 nation.co.ke\n |work        = Daily Nation, nation.co.ke\n |accessdate  = 8 January 2015\n |date        = 4 January 2014\n |url         = http://www.nation.co.ke/news/Mystery-as-Raila-son-found-dead-in-his-bed-/-/1056/2578692/-/6m8fbl/-/index.html\n |url-status  = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20150107171446/http://www.nation.co.ke/news/Mystery-as-Raila-son-found-dead-in-his-bed-/-/1056/2578692/-/6m8fbl/-/index.html\n |archivedate = 7 January 2015\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Rosemary (born 1977), Raila Jr. (born 1979) and Winnie (born 1990). Fidel was named after [[Fidel Castro]]<ref name=\"price\">Daily Nation, 2 June 2001 {{cite web |url=http://www.nationaudio.com/News/DailyNation/02062001/Features/Feature.html |title=The Price of being Raila Odinga's wife |accessdate=2008-01-01 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080128160832/http://www.nationaudio.com/News/DailyNation/02062001/Features/Feature.html |archivedate=28 January 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Winnie after [[Winnie Mandela]]. Winnie is currently studying Communication and International Area Studies as a double major student at [[Drexel University]] in [[Philadelphia]].<ref name=\"price\"/>\n\nIn an interview with [[BBC News]] in January 2008, Odinga asserted that he was the first cousin of [[United States|U.S.]] president [[Barack Obama]] through Obama's father.<ref name=\"Obama\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7176683.stm Odinga says Obama is his cousin] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316225109/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7176683.stm |date=16 March 2008 }}, [[BBC News]], 1/8/08.</ref> However, Barack Obama's paternal uncle denied any direct relation to Odinga, stating \"Odinga's mother came from this area, so it is normal for us to talk about cousins. But he is not a blood relative.\"<ref name=\"Said Obama\">[http://africa.reuters.com/wire/news/usnL08727241.html Some Kenyans forget crisis to root for Obama] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014112941/http://africa.reuters.com/wire/news/usnL08727241.html |date=14 October 2008 }}, [[Reuters]], 1/8/08.</ref>\n\nOdinga briefly played soccer for [[Luo Union]] (now [[Gor Mahia F.C.|Gor Mahia]]) as a [[Midfielder (association football)|midfielder]].<ref name=\"price\"/>\n\nOdinga was appointed by the [[African Union]] to mediate the [[2010-2011 Ivorian crisis]], which involved [[Alassane Ouattara]] and [[Laurent Gbagbo]].\nOdinga wrote \"Flame of Freedom\" a 1040 paged [[autobiography]] which talks about his life from childhood. It was launched on 6 October 2013 in [[Kenya]] and subsequently in United States on 15 October 2013. He was accompanied by a section of Kenyan county governors.\n\n==Controversy==\nDuring his premiership, Odinga appointed [[Miguna Miguna]] as his advisor on coalition affairs, whom he later suspended in August 2011,<ref>Daily Nation, 4 August 2011, [http://www.nation.co.ke/News/politics/Raila+kicks+out+key+aide/-/1064/1213684/-/irw5r6z/-/index.html Raila kick out Key aid] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518053425/http://www.nation.co.ke/News/politics/Raila+kicks+out+key+aide/-/1064/1213684/-/irw5r6z/-/index.html |date=18 May 2014 }}.</ref> citing \"gross misconduct\". The ''[[Daily Nation]]'' quoted his reason for suspension as being \"accused of misrepresenting the office of the Prime Minister, possibly a reference to his having aired strong views which may have embarrassed the PM.\" Miguna Miguna latter published controversial books about his working relationship with Odinga.\n\nHis suspension came at a time when the electoral body, the [[Interim Independent Electoral Commission of Kenya|IIEC]], was in an uproar and unsettled by anonymously authored complaints which the commissioners characterise as a hate campaign but which raise troubling questions on corruption and nepotism. Later Miguna, after suspension, issued a statement that said he \"was instructed to write my article on the IIEC chairman and the position he had taken with respect to the party's decision to kick out rebellious [[Member of Parliament|MP]]s and Councillors.\" He later denied, according to the ''[[Nairobi Star]]''.<ref>Nairobi Star. 13 August 2011. In a twist of events however there are rumours that he will stand down and let one of the CORD principals Mr. Wetangula vie for presidency and back the Jubilee Party to be launched in September 2016. Odinga was the leader of the opposition who let hundreds of people get killed for no cause. [http://www.the-star.co.ke/national/national/35896-miguna-slams-raila Miguna Slam Raila] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404163957/http://www.the-star.co.ke/national/national/35896-miguna-slams-raila |date=4 April 2012 }}.</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, in a leaked video recording, a voice of one Moses Wetangula, the then Senator of Bungoma, appeared to implicate Odinga in a gold deal gone sour, a deal in which billions of dollars were lost by the UAE king https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/news/Wetangula-says-fake-gold-scam/539546-5136278-sxisrr/index.html\n\n==Honours and awards==\n===Honorary degrees===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! University !! Country !! Honour !! style=\"width:60px;\"|Year \n|-\n| [[University of Nairobi]] || {{flag|Kenya}} || [[Doctor of Laws]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"|2008<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uonbi.ac.ke/sites/default/files/Citation%20on%20Raila.pdf |title=Citation |format=PDF |date=2008 |publisher=University of Nairobi |accessdate=12 November 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812083559/http://www.uonbi.ac.ke/sites/default/files/Citation%20on%20Raila.pdf |archivedate=12 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Florida A&M University]] || {{flag|United States}} || Honorary degree || style=\"text-align:center;\"|2012<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kenyacentral.com/feed/http://www.kenyacentral.com/general/30017-applause-as-%E2%80%98dr-odinga%E2%80%99-returns.txt |title=Kenya Online: Applause as \u2018Dr Odinga\u2019 returns |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=2012 |website=kenyacentral.com |publisher= |accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Limkokwing University of Creative Technology]] || {{flag|Malaysia}} || Doctorate of Leadership in Social Development || style=\"text-align:center;\"|2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.limkokwing.net/malaysia/community/recognized_leadership/rt._hon._raila_amolo_odinga|title=Recognized_leadership: Rt. Hon. Raila Amolo Odinga|date=2012|publisher=Limkokwing University|accessdate=12 November 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112033833/http://www.limkokwing.net/malaysia/community/recognized_leadership/rt._hon._raila_amolo_odinga|archivedate=12 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Luo people of Kenya and Tanzania]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Badejo|first=Babafemi A.|year=2006 |title=Raila Odinga: An Enigma in Kenyan Politics |location=Lagos; Nairobi|publisher= Yintab Books |isbn=9783720880}}\n*{{cite book |last=Odinga|first=Raila|last2=Elderkin|first2=Sarah |year=2013 |title=The Flame of Freedom |location=Nairobi, Kenya |publisher=Mountain Top Publishers and Worldreader |isbn=9966050582}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links | wikt=no |q=no| b=no | n=no |s=no | v=no | voy=no | species=no |d=Q57657| display=Raila Odinga}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21587054 Profile on