{"title_page": "Plasmonic lens", "text_new": "In [[nano-optics]], a '''plasmonic lens''' generally refers to a [[lens (optics)|lens]] for [[surface plasmon polariton]]s (SPPs), i.e. a device that redirects SPPs to converge towards a single [[Focus (optics)|focal point]]. Because SPPs can have very small [[wavelength]], they can converge into a very small and very intense spot, much smaller than the [[vacuum|free space]] wavelength and the [[diffraction limit]].<ref name=Liu/><ref name=srit/>\n\nA simple example of a plasmonic lens is a series of [[concentric|concentric ring]]s on a [[metal|metal film]]. Any light that hits the film from free space at a 90 degree angle, known as [[Angle of incidence (optics)|the normal]], will get coupled into a SPP (this part works like a [[diffraction grating|diffraction grating coupler]]), and that SPP will be heading towards the center of the circles, which is the focal point.<ref name=Liu>\n{{cite journal\n|doi=10.1021/nl051013j\n|title=Focusing Surface Plasmons with a Plasmonic Lens\n|year=2005\n|url=http://circuit.ucsd.edu/~zhaowei/Journals/NanoLetter_Zhaowei_SP_lens.pdf\n|format=free PDF download\n|last1=Liu|first1=Zhaowei|last2=Steele|first2=Jennifer M.|last3=Srituravanich|first3=Werayut\n|last4=Pikus|first4=Yuri|last5=Sun|first5=Cheng|last6=Zhang|first6=Xiang\n|journal=Nano Letters\n|volume=5\n|issue=9\n|pages=1726\u20139\n|pmid=16159213|bibcode = 2005NanoL...5.1726L |citeseerx=10.1.1.180.2164\n}}</ref><ref name=srit>\n{{cite journal\n|doi= 10.1038/nnano.2008.303\n|url= http://xlab.me.berkeley.edu/pdf/102.pdf\n|format=Free PDF download\n|title= Plasmonic lens in the near field for high-speed nanolithography\n|year= 2008\n|last1= Srituravanich\n|first1= Werayut\n|last2= Pan\n|first2= Liang\n|last3= Wang\n|first3= Yuan\n|last4= Sun\n|first4= Cheng\n|last5= Bogy\n|first5= David B.\n|last6= Zhang\n|first6= Xiang\n|journal= Nature Nanotechnology\n|volume= 3\n|issue= 12\n|pages= 733\u20137\n|pmid= 19057593|bibcode = 2008NatNa...3..733S }} See also [http://www.berkeley.edu/news/media/releases/2008/10/22_flyinglens.shtml Press release: Denser computer chips possible with plasmonic lenses]. UC Berkeley News. 2008-10-22</ref> Another example is a tapered \"dimple\".<ref>\"A Plasmonic Dimple Lens for Nanoscale Focusing of Light\" [https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/nl9016368 doi: 10.1021/nl9016368]</ref>\n\nIn 2007, a novel, or technologically new, '''plasmonic lens''' was proposed by [[modulation|modulating light]] through a metallic film with arrayed [[nanoparticle|nano-slits]], which have constant depth but variant widths.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Xu|first1=T.|last2=Du|first2=C.|last3=Wang|first3=C.|last4=Luo|first4=X.G.|title=Subwavelength imaging by metallic slab lens with nanoslits|journal=Applied Physics Letters|date=13 Nov 2007|volume=91|issue=20|pages=201501|doi=10.1063/1.2811711|bibcode = 2007ApPhL..91t1501X }}</ref> The slits transport [[electromagnetic energy]] in the form of SPPs in [[nanometer|nano meter]] sized [[waveguides]] and provide desired [[phase difference|phase adjustments]] for manipulating the [[light|beam of light]]. The scientists claim that it is an improvement over other [[subwavelength]] imaging techniques, such as \"[[superlens]]es\", where the object and image are confined to the [[Electromagnetic radiation#Near and far fields|near field]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dum\u00e9|first1=Belle|title=Nano-lens moves on|url=http://nanotechweb.org/cws/article/tech/33288|accessdate=Mar 10, 2008|publisher=IOP group}}</ref>\n\nThese devices have been suggested for various applications that take advantage of the small size and high intensity of the SPPs at the focal point. These include [[photolithography]],<ref name=srit/> [[heat-assisted magnetic recording]], [[microscopy]], [[biophotonics]], biological molecule sensors, and [[solar cells]], as well as other applications.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019|reason=removed citation to predatory publisher content}}\n\nThe term \"plasmonic lens\" is also sometimes used to describe something different: Any free-space lens (i.e., a lens that focuses free-space light, rather than SPPs), that has something to do with plasmonics.<ref>T. Zentgraf, Y. Liu, M. H. Mikkelsen, J. Valentine, and X. Zhang. [https://doi.org/10.1038/nnano.2010.282 \"Plasmonic Luneburg and Eaton lenses\"]. ''Nat. Nanotechnol''. 6, 151\u2013155 (2011).</ref> These often come up in discussions of [[superlens]]es.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019|reason=removed citation to predatory publisher content}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal\n|doi= 10.1038/nphoton.2012.296 \n|title= Surface plasmon resurrection\n|year= 2012\n|journal= Nature Photonics\n|volume= 6\n|issue= 11\n|page= 707|bibcode= 2012NaPho...6..707.\n|doi-access= free\n}}\n\n*{{cite journal\n|doi= 10.1364/OE.17.014270\n|url= http://8.18.37.105/oe/fulltext.cfm?uri=oe-17-16-14270&id=184274\n|format= Free article download\n|title= The role of short and long range surface plasmons for plasmonic focusing applications\n|year= 2009\n|last1= Yanai\n|first1= Avner\n|last2= Levy\n|first2= Uriel\n|journal= Optics Express\n|volume= 17\n|issue= 16\n|pages= 14270\u201380\n|pmid= 19654836|bibcode = 2009OExpr..1714270Y }}\n\n*{{cite journal\n|doi= 10.1016/j.physrep.2004.11.001 \n|url = https://scholar.google.com/scholar?cluster=12968458470485708846&hl=en&as_sdt=0,22\n|format= free PDF download\n|title= Nano-optics of surface plasmon polaritons\n|year= 2005\n|last1= Zayats\n|first1= Anatoly V.\n|last2= Smolyaninov\n|first2= Igor I.\n|last3= Maradudin\n|first3= Alexei A.\n|journal= Physics Reports\n|volume= 408\n|issue= 3\u20134\n|page= 131|bibcode = 2005PhR...408..131Z }}\n\n[[Category:Plasmonics]]\n[[Category:Biotechnology]]\n[[Category:Metamaterials]]\n[[Category:Lenses]]\n", "text_old": "In [[nano-optics]], a '''plasmonic lens''' generally refers to a [[lens (optics)|lens]] for [[surface plasmon polariton]]s (SPPs), i.e. a device that redirects SPPs to converge towards a single [[Focus (optics)|focal point]]. Because SPPs can have very small [[wavelength]], they can converge into a very small and very intense spot, much smaller than the [[vacuum|free space]] wavelength and the [[diffraction limit]].<ref name=Liu/><ref name=srit/>\n\nA simple example of a plasmonic lens is a series of [[concentric|concentric ring]]s on a [[metal|metal film]]. Any light that hits the film from free space at a 90 degree angle, known as [[Angle of incidence (optics)|the normal]], will get coupled into a SPP (this part works like a [[diffraction grating|diffraction grating coupler]]), and that SPP will be heading towards the center of the circles, which is the focal point.<ref name=Liu>\n{{cite journal\n|doi=10.1021/nl051013j\n|title=Focusing Surface Plasmons with a Plasmonic Lens\n|year=2005\n|url=http://circuit.ucsd.edu/~zhaowei/Journals/NanoLetter_Zhaowei_SP_lens.pdf\n|format=free PDF download\n|last1=Liu|first1=Zhaowei|last2=Steele|first2=Jennifer M.|last3=Srituravanich|first3=Werayut\n|last4=Pikus|first4=Yuri|last5=Sun|first5=Cheng|last6=Zhang|first6=Xiang\n|journal=Nano Letters\n|volume=5\n|issue=9\n|pages=1726\u20139\n|pmid=16159213|bibcode = 2005NanoL...5.1726L |citeseerx=10.1.1.180.2164\n}}</ref><ref name=srit>\n{{cite journal\n|doi= 10.1038/nnano.2008.303\n|url= http://xlab.me.berkeley.edu/pdf/102.pdf\n|format=Free PDF download\n|title= Plasmonic lens in the near field for high-speed nanolithography\n|year= 2008\n|last1= Srituravanich\n|first1= Werayut\n|last2= Pan\n|first2= Liang\n|last3= Wang\n|first3= Yuan\n|last4= Sun\n|first4= Cheng\n|last5= Bogy\n|first5= David B.\n|last6= Zhang\n|first6= Xiang\n|journal= Nature Nanotechnology\n|volume= 3\n|issue= 12\n|pages= 733\u20137\n|pmid= 19057593|bibcode = 2008NatNa...3..733S }} See also [http://www.berkeley.edu/news/media/releases/2008/10/22_flyinglens.shtml Press release: Denser computer chips possible with plasmonic lenses]. UC Berkeley News. 2008-10-22</ref> Another example is a tapered \"dimple\".<ref>\"A Plasmonic Dimple Lens for Nanoscale Focusing of Light\" [https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/nl9016368 doi: 10.1021/nl9016368]</ref>\n\nIn 2007, a novel, or technologically new, '''plasmonic lens''' was proposed by [[modulation|modulating light]] through a metallic film with arrayed [[nanoparticle|nano-slits]], which have constant depth but variant widths.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Xu|first1=T.|last2=Du|first2=C.|last3=Wang|first3=C.|last4=Luo|first4=X.G.|title=Subwavelength imaging by metallic slab lens with nanoslits|journal=Applied Physics Letters|date=13 Nov 2007|volume=91|issue=20|pages=201501|doi=10.1063/1.2811711|bibcode = 2007ApPhL..91t1501X }}</ref> The slits transport [[electromagnetic energy]] in the form of SPPs in [[nanometer|nano meter]] sized [[waveguides]] and provide desired [[phase difference|phase adjustments]] for manipulating the [[light|beam of light]]. The scientists claim that it is an improvement over other [[subwavelength]] imaging techniques, such as \"[[superlens]]es\", where the object and image are confined to the [[Electromagnetic radiation#Near and far fields|near field]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dum\u00e9|first1=Belle|title=Nano-lens moves on|url=http://nanotechweb.org/cws/article/tech/33288|accessdate=Mar 10, 2008|publisher=IOP group}}</ref>\n\nThese devices have been suggested for various applications that take advantage of the small size and high intensity of the SPPs at the focal point. These include [[photolithography]],<ref name=srit/> [[heat-assisted magnetic recording]], [[microscopy]], [[biophotonics]], biological molecule sensors, and [[solar cells]], as well as other applications.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019|reason=removed citation to predatory publisher content}}\n\nThe term \"plasmonic lens\" is also sometimes used to describe something different: Any free-space lens (i.e., a lens that focuses free-space light, rather than SPPs), that has something to do with plasmonics.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019|reason=removed citation to predatory publisher content}}  These often come up in discussions of [[superlens]]es.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019|reason=removed citation to predatory publisher content}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal\n|doi= 10.1038/nphoton.2012.296 \n|title= Surface plasmon resurrection\n|year= 2012\n|journal= Nature Photonics\n|volume= 6\n|issue= 11\n|page= 707|bibcode= 2012NaPho...6..707.\n|doi-access= free\n}}\n\n*{{cite journal\n|doi= 10.1364/OE.17.014270\n|url= http://8.18.37.105/oe/fulltext.cfm?uri=oe-17-16-14270&id=184274\n|format= Free article download\n|title= The role of short and long range surface plasmons for plasmonic focusing applications\n|year= 2009\n|last1= Yanai\n|first1= Avner\n|last2= Levy\n|first2= Uriel\n|journal= Optics Express\n|volume= 17\n|issue= 16\n|pages= 14270\u201380\n|pmid= 19654836|bibcode = 2009OExpr..1714270Y }}\n\n*{{cite journal\n|doi= 10.1016/j.physrep.2004.11.001 \n|url = https://scholar.google.com/scholar?cluster=12968458470485708846&hl=en&as_sdt=0,22\n|format= free PDF download\n|title= Nano-optics of surface plasmon polaritons\n|year= 2005\n|last1= Zayats\n|first1= Anatoly V.\n|last2= Smolyaninov\n|first2= Igor I.\n|last3= Maradudin\n|first3= Alexei A.\n|journal= Physics Reports\n|volume= 408\n|issue= 3\u20134\n|page= 131|bibcode = 2005PhR...408..131Z }}\n\n[[Category:Plasmonics]]\n[[Category:Biotechnology]]\n[[Category:Metamaterials]]\n[[Category:Lenses]]\n", "name_user": "Floridorus", "label": "safe", "comment": "source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plasmonic_lens"}
{"title_page": "West Canary skink", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = West Canary skink\n| image = Chalcides viridanus (Wroclaw zoo).JPG\n| status = LC \n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=iucn>[[Jose Antonio Mateo Miras|Miras JAM]], [[Valentin P\u00e9rez-Mellado|P\u00e9rez-Mellado V]], [[I\u00f1igo Mart\u00ednez-Solano|Mart\u00ednez-Solano I]] (2009). \"''Chalcides viridanus'' \". The [[IUCN]] Red List of Threatened Species 2009: e.T61490A12480456. https://dx.doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2009.RLTS.T61490A12480456.en. Downloaded on 29 April 2020.</ref>\n| taxon = Chalcides viridanus\n| authority = ([[Johann Ludwig Christian Gravenhorst|Gravenhorst]], 1851)\n| range_map = Chalcides viridanus distribution.png\n| synonyms = *''Gongylus viridanus'' <br>{{small|Gravenhorst, 1851}}\n*''Chalcides viridanus'' <br>{{small|\u2014 [[George Albert Boulenger|Boulenger]], 1887}}\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=RDB/>\n}}\n\nThe '''West Canary skink''' (''Chalcides viridanus''), also known [[Common name|commonly]] as the '''Canaryan cylindrical skink''', '''East Canary Islands skink''',  the '''Tenerife skink''', and '''''lisa dorada''''' in Spanish, is a [[species]] of [[lizard]] in the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Scincidae]]. The species is [[Endemism|endemic]] to the [[Canary Islands]].\n\n==Habitat==\nThe natural [[habitat]]s of ''C. viridanus'' are temperate [[forest]], temperate [[shrubland]], subtropical or tropical dry shrubland, [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]-type shrubby vegetation, temperate [[grassland]], rocky areas, rocky shores, sandy shores, [[arable land]], pastureland, rural gardens, and [[urban area]]s. It is found at altitudes up to {{convert|2,000|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=iucn/> \n\n==Description==\n''C. viridanus'' may reach a total length (including tail) of about {{convert|18|cm|in|abbr=on}}. \n\n==Behavior==\n''C. viridanus'' is active during the day and at dusk. Both its life in nature and its requirements in a [[terrarium]] are very similar to those of the [[Chalcides sexlineatus|Gran Canaria skink]].\n\n==Reproduction==\n''C. viridanus'' is [[Viviparity|viviparous]].<ref name=RDB>{{EMBL species|genus=Chalcides|species=viridanus}} www.reptile-database.org.</ref>\n\n==Geographic range==\n''C. viridianus'' is found on the following Canary Islands: [[Tenerife]], [[El Hierro]], Roque de Garachico, and Roque de Agna.\n<!-- *''Chalcides viridianus coeruleopunctatus'' Salvador, 1975 \u2013 [[La Gomera]] (elevated to species-->\n\n==Sources==\n(listed chronologically)\n*[[Richard P. Brown|Brown RP]], [[Roger Stephen Thorpe|Thorpe RS]], [[Ana Mar\u00eda B\u00e1ez|B\u00e1ez M]] (1991). \"Parallel within-island microevolution of lizards on neighbouring islands\". ''Nature'' '''352''': 60\u201362.\n*Brown RP, Thorpe RS, B\u00e1ez M (1993). \"Patterns and causes of morphological population differentiation in the Tenerife skink, ''Chalcides viridanus'' \". ''Biological Journal of the Linnean Society'' '''50''' (4): 313\u2013328.\n*Brown RP, [[Jose Pestano|Pestano J]] (1998). \"Phylogeography of Canary Island skinks inferred from mtDNA sequences\". ''Molecular Ecology'' '''7''': 1183\u20131191.\n*Brown RP, Campos-Delgado R, Pestano J (2000). \"Mitochondrial DNA evolution and population history of the Tenerife skink ''Chalcides viridanus'' \". ''Molecular Ecology'' '''9''': 1061\u20131069.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[George Albert Boulenger|Boulenger GA]] (1887). ''Catalogue of the Lizards in the British Museum (Natural History). Second Edition. Volume III. ... Scincid\u00e6 ....'' London: Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History). (Taylor and Francis, printers). xii + 575 pp. + Plates I-XL. (''Chalcides viridanus'', new combination, p. 402).\n*[[Johann Ludwig Christian Gravenhorst|Gravenhorst JLC]] (1851). \"''\u00dcber die im Zoologischen Museum der Universit\u00e4t Breslau befindlichen Wirtelschleichen ''(Pseudosaura)'', Kr\u00fcppelf\u00fcssler ''(Brachypoda)'' und einige andere, denselben verwandte Reptilien aus dem Z\u00fcnften der Schleichen und Dickz\u00fcngler'' \". ''Nova Acta Academiae Caesarae Leopoldina Carolinae Germaninicae Naturae'' '''23''' (1): 291\u2013394. (''Gongylus viridanus'', new species, pp. 348\u2013350 + Plate XXXV, figures 1\u20136). (in German).\n\n==External links==\n*Photo [https://www.biolib.cz/cz/taxon/id164684/]\n\n{{Commons|Chalcides viridanus}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2006815}}\n\n[[Category:Reptiles of the Canary Islands]]\n[[Category:Chalcides]]\n[[Category:Reptiles described in 1851]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Johann Ludwig Christian Gravenhorst]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{skink-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = West Canary skink\n| image = Chalcides viridanus (Wroclaw zoo).JPG\n| status = LC \n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=iucn>[[Jose Antonio Mateo Miras|Miras JAM]], [[Valentin P\u00e9rez-Mellado|P\u00e9rez-Mellado V]], [[I\u00f1igo Mart\u00ednez-Solano|Mart\u00ednez-Solano I]] (2009). \"''Chalcides viridanus'' \". The [[IUCN]] Red List of Threatened Species 2009: e.T61490A12480456. https://dx.doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2009.RLTS.T61490A12480456.en. Downloaded on 29 April 2020.</ref>\n| taxon = Chalcides viridanus\n| authority = ([[Johann Ludwig Christian Gravenhorst|Gravenhorst]], 1851)\n| range_map = Chalcides viridanus distribution.png\n| synonyms = *''Gongylus viridanus'' <br>{{small|Gravenhorst, 1851}}\n*''Chalcides viridanus'' <br>{{small|\u2014 [[George Albert Boulenger|Boulenger]], 1887}}\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=RDB/>\n}}\n\nThe '''West Canary skink''' (''Chalcides viridanus''), also known [[Common name|commonly]] as the '''Canaryan cylindrical skink''', '''East Canary Islands skink''',  the '''Tenerife skink''', and '''''lisa dorada''''' in Spanish, is a [[species]] of [[lizard]] in the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Scincidae]]. The species is [[Endemism|endemic]] to the [[Canary Islands]].\n\n==Habitat==\nThe natural [[habitat]]s of ''C. viridanus'' are temperate [[forest]], temperate [[shrubland]], subtropical or tropical dry shrubland, [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]-type shrubby vegetation, temperate [[grassland]], rocky areas, rocky shores, sandy shores, [[arable land]], pastureland, rural gardens, and [[urban area]]s. It is found at altitudes up to {{convert|2,000|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=iucn/> \n\n==Description==\n''C. viridanus'' may reach a total length (including tail) of about {{convert|18|cm|in|abbr=on}}. \n\n==Behavior==\n''C. viridanus'' is active during the day and at dusk. Both its life in nature and its requirements in a [[terrarium]] are very similar to those of the [[Chalcides sexlineatus|Gran Canaria skink]].\n\n==Reproduction==\n''C. viridanus'' is [[Viviparity|viviparous]].<ref name=RDB>{{EMBL species|genus=Chalcides|species=viridanus}} www.reptile-database.org.</ref>\n\n==Geographic range==\n''C. viridianus'' is found on the following Canary Islands: [[Tenerife]], [[El Hierro]], Roque de Garachico, and Roque de Agna.\n<!-- *''Chalcides viridianus coeruleopunctatus'' Salvador, 1975 \u2013 [[La Gomera]] (elevated to species-->\n\n==Sources==\n(listed chronologically)\n*[[Richard P. Brown|Brown RP]], [[Roger Stephen Thorpe|Thorpe RS]], [[Ana Mar\u00eda B\u00e1ez|B\u00e1ez M]] (1991). \"Parallel within-island microevolution of lizards on neighbouring islands\". ''Nature'' '''352''': 60\u201362.\n*Brown RP, Thorpe RS, B\u00e1ez M (1993). \"Patterns and causes of morphological population differentiation in the Tenerife skink, ''Chalcides viridanus'' \". ''Biological Journal of the Linnean Society'' '''50''' (4): 313\u2013328.\n*Brown RP, [[Jose Pestano|Pestano J]] (1998). \"Phylogeography of Canary Island skinks inferred from mtDNA sequences\". ''Molecular Ecology'' '''7''': 1183\u20131191.\n*Brown RP, Campos-Delgado R, Pestano J (2000). \"Mitochondrial DNA evolution and population history of the Tenerife skink ''Chalcides viridanus'' \". ''Molecular Ecology'' '''9''': 1061\u20131069.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[George Albert Boulenger|Boulenger GA]] (1887). ''Catalogue of the Lizards in the British Museum (Natural History). Second Edition. Volume III. ... Scincid\u00e6 ....'' London: Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History). (Taylor and Francis, printers). xii + 575 pp. + Plates I-XL. (''Chalcides viridanus'', new combination, p. 402).\n*[[Johann Ludwig Christian Gravenhorst|Gravenhorst JLC]] (1851). \"''\u00dcber die im Zoologischen Museum der Universit\u00e4t Breslau befindlichen Wirtelschleichen ''(Pseudosaura)'', Kr\u00fcppelf\u00fcssler ''(Brachypoda)'' und einige andere, denselben verwandte Reptilien aus dem Z\u00fcnften der Schleichen und Dickz\u00fcngler''\". ''Nova Acta Academiae Caesarae Leopoldina Carolinae Germaninicae Naturae'' '''23''' (1): 291\u2013394. (''Gongylus viridanus'', new species, pp. 348\u2013350 + Plate XXXV, figures 1\u20136). (in German).\n\n==External links==\n*Photo [https://www.biolib.cz/cz/taxon/id164684/]\n\n{{Commons|Chalcides viridanus}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2006815}}\n\n[[Category:Reptiles of the Canary Islands]]\n[[Category:Chalcides]]\n[[Category:Reptiles described in 1851]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Johann Ludwig Christian Gravenhorst]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{skink-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lyttle-Wight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Canary_skink"}
{"title_page": "Vindu Dara Singh", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image=Vindu_dara_singh cropped.jpg\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1964|05|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n| yearsactive = 1994\u2013present\n| height = 1.82 m\n| occupation = [[Actor]]\n| father = [[Dara Singh]]\n| spouse = [[Farah (actress)|Farah Naaz]] (m. 1996\u20132002)<br />Dina Umarova (m. 2005\u2013present) \n|relatives   = See [[List of Hindi film clans#Randhawa family|Randhawa family]]\n| children = 2 including Fateh Randhawa & Ameila Randhawa \n}}\n\n'''Virendra Singh Randhawa''' better known as '''Vindu Dara Singh''' (6 May 1964) is an Indian film and television actor. He is the winner of [[Bigg Boss (Season 3)|the third season]] of ''[[Bigg Boss]]''.\n\n==Career==\nVindu made his acting debut in the 1994 Hindi film ''[[Karan (1994 film)|Karan]]''. Then he acted in 1996 [[Cinema of Punjab|Punjabi]] film, ''Rab Dian Rakhan'' which was directed by his father. Since then, he has acted in many films, mostly in supporting roles.\n\nHe has also acted in TV serials, including the role of [[Hanuman]] in the TV serial ''Jai Veer Hanuman'', much like his father did in [[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]. He has also starred as a [[supervillain]] in TV serials on [[Star Plus]], including Zaal in ''[[Ssshhhh...Koi Hai]]'' ([[2003 in television|2003]]) and Char Sau Chalis in ''Karma'' ([[2004 in television|2004]]). Vindu has also played an important role in the serial \"Black\" on [[9X (TV channel)|9X]] where he has played the character of Rajiv, a medium who can establish connections with spirits. Vindu Dara Singh has made appearance in television shows like ''[[MasterChef India (season 2)|Master Chef 2]]'', ''[[Comedy Circus]]'', ''All Most Famous'', ''Maa Exchange''. Singh also paired in a [[Pepsi]] commercial with [[Ranbir Kapoor]].\n\nHe was the winner of the third season of the reality TV show ''[[Bigg Boss]]'' in 2009 and was also announced the most stylish and bold contestant to win the [[Chevrolet Cruze]] a feat that has never occurred winning both the cash prize and car, defeating [[Pravesh Rana]] and [[Poonam Dhillon]]. He has been given the title 'Bade dil wala' (man with a golden heart) by his housemates.\n\nVindu Dara Singh has also worked in many successful films like ''[[Garv]]'', ''[[Maine Pyaar Kyun Kiya]]'', ''[[Partner (2007 film)|Partner]]'', ''[[Khushboo (2008 film)|Khushboo]]'', ''[[Team - The Force]]'', ''[[Kisse Pyaar Karoon]]'', ''[[Kambakkht Ishq]]'', ''Maruti'', ''[[Housefull (2010 film)|Housefull]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Vindu dara and dina.jpg|thumb|Vindu and his wife Dina Umarova]]\nVindu's is son of the wrestler-turned-actor and Member of Parliament [[Dara Singh]]. He was married to [[Farah (actress)|Farah]], with whom he had a son Fateh but later they divorced, and subsequently married model Dina Umarova, with whom he has a daughter Amelia.<ref>{{cite web|title='I hope I'm as lucky as Shilpa'|url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2009/dec/281209-vindu-hopes-good-luck.htm|publisher=mid-day|accessdate=2011-06-13|author=IANS|date=27 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nVindu has acted in Hindi, Punjabi, Telegu, Gujrati, Bhojpuri films and has also acted on stage in live plays.\nVindu has his studio in Chandigarh mohali called Dara Studio and he & his wife have one of the most successful Global Nail brands distribution in India called Bluesky .\n\n==Filmography==\n\n*''[[Karan (1994 film)|Karan]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Garv]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Maine Pyaar Kyun Kiya]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Partner (2007 film)|Partner]]'' (2007)\n*''[[Khushboo (2008 film)|Khushboo]]'' (2008)\n*''Team - The Force''\n*''[[Kisse Pyaar Karoon]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Kambakkht Ishq]]'' (2009)\n*''Maruti''\n*''[[Mujhse Shaadi Karogi]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Housefull (2010 film)|Housefull]]'' (2010)\n*''[[The Lion of Punjab (film)|The Lion of Punjab]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Sri Rama Rajyam]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Housefull 2]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Joker (2012 film)|Joker]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Son of Sardaar]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Himmatwala (2013 film)|Himmatwala]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Mahabharat Aur Barbareek|Mahabharat Aur Barbareek]]'' (2013) as [[Hanuman]]\nlove you Soniye ( 2013)\n*''[[Jatt James Bond]]'' (2014)\nBillu Gamer (2016)\nNanak Naam jahaz hai (2020)\nNidar (2020)\n\n==Dubbing roles==\n===Animated films===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Film Title !! Original Voice !! Character !! Dub Language !! Original Language !! Original Year Release !! Dub Year Release !! Notes\n|-\n| [[The Incredibles]] || [[Samuel L. Jackson]] || [[List of The Incredibles characters#Frozone|Lucius Best / Frozone]]<br>'''(Barfila)''' || Hindi || English || 2004 || 2004 || The Hindi dub released as<br> '''\"Hum Hain Lajawab\"'''.<br>[[Vrajesh Hirjee]] dubbed this character in [[Incredibles 2|sequel]].\n|-\n|}Billu Gamer\n\n==Television==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Programme !! Role\n|-yug\n|''[[Draupadi (2001 TV series)|Draupadi]]'' (2001) || [[Bheema]]\n|-\n|''[[Ssshhhh...Koi Hai]]'' (2003) || Zaal\n|-\n|''[[Bigg Boss 3]]'' (2009) || Himself (WINNER)\n|-\n|''[[Maa Exchange]]'' (2011)|| Himself\n|-\n|''[[Welcome - Baazi Mehmaan-Nawaazi ki]]'' (2013)  || Himself\n|-\n|''[[Mrs. Kaushik Ki Paanch Bahuein]]'' (2013) || Bhushan (Foolish Man)\n|-\n|''[[Power Couple]]'' (2015)|| Himself\n|-\n|''[[Jai Veer Hanuman]]'' || [[Hanuman]]\n|-\n|''[[Betaal Pachisi (1997 TV series)|Betaal Pachisi]]'' (1997) || Zulmato\n|-\n|''[[Chandramukhi (2008 TV Seriel ) |Chandramukhi]]'' (2008)\n|| Kunwar Bhanu Pratap Singh\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* [http://realitypost.in/bigg-boss-3-winner-vindu-dara-singh-roped-rudra-ke-rakshak/ Vindu Dara Singh to perform in a Ramleela]\n* Punjabi and Hindi play (Hello Darling)\n* Golmaal the play Hindi\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Vindu Dara Singh}}\n* {{official website|http://www.vindudarasingh.net/}}\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2738083/ Vindu Dara Singh] on [[IMDb]]\n\n\n{{Bigg Boss}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Vindu Dara}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Indian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Indian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Punjabi cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi television]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Bigg Boss contestants]]\n[[Category:Big Brother (franchise) winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image=Vindu_dara_singh cropped.jpg\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1964|05|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n| yearsactive = 1994\u2013present\n| height = 1.82 m\n| occupation = [[Actor]]\n| father = [[Dara Singh]]\n| spouse = [[Farah (actress)|Farah Naaz]] (m. 1996 - 2002)<br />Dina Umarova (m. 2005 - present) \n|relatives   = See [[List of Hindi film clans#Randhawa family|Randhawa family]]\n| children = 2 including Fateh Randhawa & Ameila Randhawa \n}}\n\n'''Virendra Singh Randhawa''' better known as '''Vindu Dara Singh''' (6 May 1964) is an Indian film and television actor. He is the winner of [[Bigg Boss (Season 3)|the third season]] of ''[[Bigg Boss]]''.\n\n==Career==\nVindu made his acting debut in the 1994 Hindi film ''[[Karan (1994 film)|Karan]]''. Then he acted in 1996 [[Cinema of Punjab|Punjabi]] film, ''Rab Dian Rakhan'' which was directed by his father. Since then, he has acted in many films, mostly in supporting roles.\n\nHe has also acted in TV serials, including the role of [[Hanuman]] in the TV serial ''Jai Veer Hanuman'', much like his father did in [[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]. He has also starred as a [[supervillain]] in TV serials on [[Star Plus]], including Zaal in ''[[Ssshhhh...Koi Hai]]'' ([[2003 in television|2003]]) and Char Sau Chalis in ''Karma'' ([[2004 in television|2004]]). Vindu has also played an important role in the serial \"Black\" on [[9X (TV channel)|9X]] where he has played the character of Rajiv, a medium who can establish connections with spirits. Vindu Dara Singh has made appearance in television shows like ''[[MasterChef India (season 2)|Master Chef 2]]'', ''[[Comedy Circus]]'', ''All Most Famous'', ''Maa Exchange''. Singh also paired in a [[Pepsi]] commercial with [[Ranbir Kapoor]].\n\nHe was the winner of the third season of the reality TV show ''[[Bigg Boss]]'' in 2009 and was also announced the most stylish and bold contestant to win the [[Chevrolet Cruze]] a feat that has never occurred winning both the cash prize and car, defeating [[Pravesh Rana]] and [[Poonam Dhillon]]. He has been given the title 'Bade dil wala' (man with a golden heart) by his housemates.\n\nVindu Dara Singh has also worked in many successful films like ''[[Garv]]'', ''[[Maine Pyaar Kyun Kiya]]'', ''[[Partner (2007 film)|Partner]]'', ''[[Khushboo (2008 film)|Khushboo]]'', ''[[Team - The Force]]'', ''[[Kisse Pyaar Karoon]]'', ''[[Kambakkht Ishq]]'', ''Maruti'', ''[[Housefull (2010 film)|Housefull]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Vindu dara and dina.jpg|thumb|Vindu and his wife Dina Umarova]]\nVindu's is son of the wrestler-turned-actor and Member of Parliament [[Dara Singh]]. He was married to [[Farah (actress)|Farah]], with whom he had a son Fateh but later they divorced, and subsequently married model Dina Umarova, with whom he has a daughter Amelia.<ref>{{cite web|title='I hope I'm as lucky as Shilpa'|url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2009/dec/281209-vindu-hopes-good-luck.htm|publisher=mid-day|accessdate=2011-06-13|author=IANS|date=27 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nVindu has acted in Hindi, Punjabi, Telegu, Gujrati, Bhojpuri films and has also acted on stage in live plays.\nVindu has his studio in Chandigarh mohali called Dara Studio and he & his wife have one of the most successful Global Nail brands distribution in India called Bluesky .\n\n==Filmography==\n\n*''[[Karan (1994 film)|Karan]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Garv]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Maine Pyaar Kyun Kiya]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Partner (2007 film)|Partner]]'' (2007)\n*''[[Khushboo (2008 film)|Khushboo]]'' (2008)\n*''Team - The Force''\n*''[[Kisse Pyaar Karoon]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Kambakkht Ishq]]'' (2009)\n*''Maruti''\n*''[[Mujhse Shaadi Karogi]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Housefull (2010 film)|Housefull]]'' (2010)\n*''[[The Lion of Punjab (film)|The Lion of Punjab]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Sri Rama Rajyam]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Housefull 2]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Joker (2012 film)|Joker]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Son of Sardaar]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Himmatwala (2013 film)|Himmatwala]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Mahabharat Aur Barbareek|Mahabharat Aur Barbareek]]'' (2013) as [[Hanuman]]\nlove you Soniye ( 2013)\n*''[[Jatt James Bond]]'' (2014)\nBillu Gamer (2016)\nNanak Naam jahaz hai (2020)\nNidar (2020)\n\n==Dubbing roles==\n===Animated films===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Film Title !! Original Voice !! Character !! Dub Language !! Original Language !! Original Year Release !! Dub Year Release !! Notes\n|-\n| [[The Incredibles]] || [[Samuel L. Jackson]] || [[List of The Incredibles characters#Frozone|Lucius Best / Frozone]]<br>'''(Barfila)''' || Hindi || English || 2004 || 2004 || The Hindi dub released as<br> '''\"Hum Hain Lajawab\"'''.<br>[[Vrajesh Hirjee]] dubbed this character in [[Incredibles 2|sequel]].\n|-\n|}Billu Gamer\n\n==Television==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Programme !! Role\n|-yug\n|''[[Draupadi (2001 TV series)|Draupadi]]'' (2001) || [[Bheema]]\n|-\n|''[[Ssshhhh...Koi Hai]]'' (2003) || Zaal\n|-\n|''[[Bigg Boss 3]]'' (2009) || Himself (WINNER)\n|-\n|''[[Maa Exchange]]'' (2011)|| Himself\n|-\n|''[[Welcome - Baazi Mehmaan-Nawaazi ki]]'' (2013)  || Himself\n|-\n|''[[Mrs. Kaushik Ki Paanch Bahuein]]'' (2013) || Bhushan (Foolish Man)\n|-\n|'